<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / International Company News: Unilever sets its sights on
satisfying Mrs Jones - The new co-chairman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is not often that a change at the top of a well-managed multinational as
big as Unilever coincides neatly with a shift in the company's direction.
But Michael Perry, who this week succeeded Sir Michael Angus as British
co-chairman of the Anglo-Dutch consumer products manufacturer, talks like a
man who stands on the verge of a new era.
'If you ask what characterised the Angus years, clearly it was the
single-minded focus on improving Unilever's profitability by driving out
inefficiency and low margin businesses,' Mr Perry says.
Boosting the bottom line will remain as important as ever - his aim is to
improve on last year's 8.7 per cent operating margin by 'a percentage point
or two' during his four-year chairmanship. 'But it will have to happen by
different means,' he says.
The challenge now is to move forward by seizing the initiative much more
aggressively in all Unilever's markets: 'We have got to do better than our
competitors and better than we have ever done before at harnessing our
global technological resources to individual markets. It's my firm belief
that restoring the all-important focus on leading and setting the agenda is
what it's all about.'
That does not imply any let-up on cost cutting. In Europe, where Unilever is
rationalising extensively its food business to prepare for the single
market, Mr Perry says the biggest pay-off is still to come: 'You ain't seen
nothing yet. There's a hell of a lot more to come in margin improvement.'
Unilever is also still ploughing a lot of effort into straightening out US
businesses acquired in the 1980s. Profitability at its Cheseborough Ponds
subsidiary should be 'exactly where we want it in the next 12 months or so'.
The big wave of restructuring, disposals and acquisitions of the 1980s, when
Unilever shed many established businesses and expanded into new ones such as
perfumes and cosmetics, is unlikely to be repeated. Further acquisitions are
likely to be closely related to the company's four 'core businesses' of
food, detergents, personal products and speciality chemicals.
One imperative dominates the 58-year-old Mr Perry's strategic vision for
Unilever. It is sharply to accelerate the company's rate of innovation,
showering markets worldwide with new products.
The goal is particularly urgent because some of Unilever's biggest
traditional businesses - notably edible fats, in which it is the world
market leader - have grown mature and face increasingly tough price
competition. To restore margins and growth, the company needs to diversify
into new products with higher added value.
Mr Perry is counting heavily on Unilever's extensive investments in modern
information technology to tighten internal communications. But its ability
to innovate and respond faster will depend, above all, on the success of
radical moves under way to reorganise some of its biggest operations.
These have gone furthest in detergents, where Unilever's previous patchwork
of national baronies has been replaced by a more unified executive intended
to drive the business worldwide. A slightly less sweeping shake-up has been
instituted in European foods, while the personal products division is
seeking to co-ordinate its operations more closely from an office recently
established in Paris.
Although Mr Perry is satisfied with results to date, he admits that the
company is still experimenting. The trick will be to strike a balance which
produces coherent global strategies without endangering Unilever's
much-prized entrepreneurship in the field. As Mr Perry puts it: 'Innovation
and creativity only happen successfully close to markets - not in Brussels
or any other central place.'
Above all, it is essential to keep attention riveted on the consumer. 'The
moment you focus anywhere else, you are lost. Everything that drives you
must be with the sight of Mrs Jones looking you straight in the eye. If you
get that right, all the rest will be in place.'
If Mr Perry has his way, the Unilever of the 1990s will reach more Mrs
Joneses in more countries than ever before, as its reliance on Europe - 60
per cent of its business today - is gradually diminished by faster growth in
other parts of the world.
He is particularly excited by prospects in South America, south-east Asia,
India and China, where he is going in September for 'a first-hand look see'.
China, he says, will be the biggest growth market of them all 'if things
come together, if there are no more Tiananmen Squares'.
Meanwhile, Unilever will keep plugging away at the more mature markets of
the US, Europe and Japan. Although it has yet to show a profit in Japan, Mr
Perry says the company cannot afford not to be in one of the world's most
innovative markets. However, he concedes that Unilever needs to focus its
operations there more selectively.
His expansionist vision owes much to a 35-year career with Unilever which
has included postings in the Netherlands, Thailand, Argentina and Japan. He
expects his international experience - far more varied than that of Sir
Michael Angus - to be a big advantage in steering Unilever through the
challenges of the 1990s.
A self-confessed hands-on manager, whose biggest anxiety is not to grow
remote from the business, he also relishes getting out and meeting people
around the world. 'I've got to be down there talking to people, walking
through stores, looking at what my competitors are doing, sniffing around.
Not second-guessing management, but just asking them bloody tough questions
and making sure they've got sensible answers.'
</TEXT>
