<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / International Company News: Loblaw will push into US if bid
for Steinberg fails
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IF Loblaw, Canada's biggest food distributor, fails to buy the Steinberg
chain in Quebec soon, it will push further into the US, said Mr Galen
Weston, chairman of Loblaw's parent company, George Weston.
Loblaw is negotiating with Steinberg's owners for all or part of its
Montreal operations. It is the third time Loblaw has tried to enter the
Quebec grocery market over the past 20 years.
It already has a large automated bakery in Montreal.
Mr Weston said his group has CDollars 500m (USDollars 420m) or more
available for a Canadian or US acquisition. Its north-eastern US bakery
operation is succeeding after a restructuring and is expanding its long-term
supply contracts.
The Weston group has large cash resources but its earnings are being held
down by its forest products and fisheries divisions. First-quarter earnings
fell nearly 50 per cent to CDollars 6.1m on revenues of CDollars 2.5bn.
</TEXT>
