<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / International Company News: Sandvik plans expansion in
metal-cutting tools
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SANDVIK, the Swedish engineering group, is hoping to expand its presence in
the SKr50bn (Dollars 8.45bn) world metal-cutting tool market over the next
five years through acquisitions of specialist companies and internal product
development.
The Sandvik Coromant division, which had sales last year of SKr4.88bn, is
the world's largest producer of cemented-carbide tools, but has a relatively
small presence in high-speed steel tools.
Each sector accounts for half the total market, and Mr Clas Ake Hedstrom,
Sandvik Coromant president, predicted this week the company would have 'a
bigger chunk' of business in high-speed steel, and in small-hole drilling
tools, in five years.
The company already produces 12,000-13,000 types of tools, of which around
1,500 are replaced each year. But Mr Hedstrom wants to be able to serve the
needs of big manufacturing customers that use both types of cutting tool.
Mr Hedstrom said there were a number of small cutting tool companies with a
specialised product or market which could come up for sale.
But he doubted whether Coromant would acquire Valenite, the big US tool
company, because the two companies lacked the necessary product and
marketing fit.
Valenite's owner, the US telecommunications group GTE, said in September it
was considering various options including the sale of its electrical
products group, which includes precision materials.
Mr Hedstrom also wants to increase the proportion of Coromant's sales which
derive from fast-growing automation products such as tool changing systems.
These currently account for 10 per cent of sales, but also have a beneficial
knock-on effect on sales of consumable cutting tools known as 'inserts'.
Coromant's sales fell 7 per cent last year, with Germany the last European
market to succumb to the downturn. Mr Hedstrom indicated the German outlook
was clouded by the current political and industrial uncertainty, but said
the US market for consumable cutting-tools had 'passed the bottom'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
