<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / International Company News: Unilever steps up European
expansion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNILEVER, the Anglo-Dutch consumer products company, plans to increase
further its presence in central Europe by making three more acquisitions in
Poland and Czechoslovakia this year.
If the deals go through on schedule, Unilever expects to expand its annual
sales in Poland, Czechoslovakia and Hungary from about Pounds 200m (Dollars
356m) this year to almost Pounds 700m in less than five years. Without the
planned acquisitions, sales in the region would rise to almost Pounds 500m.
The deals involve the purchase of a margarine and food manufacturing
business in Poland, and of foods, detergents and soap operations in
Czechoslovakia. Total investment, including planned spending on plant
modernisation, would be almost Dollars 70m.
Mr Hans Eggerstedt, Unilever's regional director for continental Europe,
said negotiations on all the deals had been completed and were awaiting
approval by the Polish and Czech governments.
He said the investments would largely complete the company's acquisition
drive in Poland, Czechoslovakia and Hungary, and that any further deals
would be small.
He said more than three-quarters of Unilever's sales in central Europe were
locally produced. Its operations in the region would be profitable in five
years if they achieved their growth targets.
The acquisitions would make Unilever one of the most active western
investors in central Europe.
They would come on top of the Dollars 120m which it has invested, or agreed
to invest, in central Europe since it began acquiring there last year.
Its first acquisition was of an 80 per cent stake in Lever Polska, a Polish
detergents producer. In Hungary, Unilever this year bought the ice cream
business of the state-owned VMTV dairies.
Background, Page 32
