<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / International Company News: Salomon warns of extra
provisions for bond affair
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SALOMON INC, the New York securities house, warned yesterday it expected to
make new provisions, on top of the Dollars 200m already set aside, to cover
a settlement with the US government of last year's bond trading scandal.
The announcement came as it reported a drop in first-quarter net income  -
from Dollars 273m, or Dollars 2.30 a share, to Dollars 190m, or Dollars 1.51
a share - as repercussions from the scandal continued to drag down its
earnings.
Salomon reserved Dollars 200m in the third quarter of last year to cover the
likely fines, damages and other costs of settling the bond scandal with
government regulatory authorities and private parties suing the firm.
It said yesterday that although the outcome of its negotiations with the
government was uncertain, it believed any agreed resolution would require an
additional charge, to be taken after the first quarter. However, it did not
expect this charge to 'adversely affect the long-term economic prospects of
the company'.
Salomon's lawyers have been discussing a settlement with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, the government agency investigating the bond scandal,
since February. The SEC has faced strong pressure from Congress to impose a
large fine on the firm, which has admitted to falsifying bids in Treasury
bond auctions.
Salomon gave no indication when a settlement might be reached. Uncertainty
over the outcome has made many clients wary of giving business to Salomon in
sensitive areas such as investment banking and the underwriting of new
issues of equity.
This was reflected in its first-quarter earnings decline, which contrasted
sharply with the record income figures reported by several Wall Street
rivals, which have been enjoying a boom in the issuance of new corporate
equity and debt.
Salomon Brothers, the group's securities arm, reported earnings before tax
of Dollars 374m, down 26 per cent from the Dollars 503m reported a year ago.
However, the firm said its securities trading and debt underwriting results
were 'highly satisfactory'.
Phibro Energy, its oil subsidiary, reported a pre-tax loss of Dollars 30m,
compared with profits of Dollars 5m a year ago, due to weak demand for crude
oil and refined products, narrow refining margins and relatively low price
volatility.
It also warned it might be unable to recover the Dollars 116m it has
invested in Russian oil development and production joint ventures, due to
unfavourable Russian taxes and pipeline tariffs, as well as unpaid balances
due from various Russian entities.
Nevertheless, analysts were pleasantly surprised by the cost-cutting
achieved by the new management team at Salomon, headed by chairman Mr Warren
Buffett. It has radically overhauled its management systems and pay
structures since last autumn. Non-interest expenses in the quarter totalled
Dollars 584m, compared with Dollars 696m a year ago, while revenue net of
interest expense dropped from Dollars 1.18bn to Dollars 915m.
Mr Perrin Long, analyst with First of Michigan, said the cost reduction
figures were 'quite positive for the future'. He said any additional
provisions for the scandal were 'highly unlikely to significantly impair
Salomon's operating ability'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
