FT  07 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Meggitt bids Pounds 17.3m for Micrelec
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MEGGITT, the specialist engineering group, yesterday announced an agreed bid
for Micrelec Group, valuing the USM-traded petrol pump controls company at
Pounds 17.3m.
The offer of 141 new Meggitt shares for every 100 Micrelec values the
target's shares at 130p, against last night's close of 122p, up 10p.
There is a cash alternative of 62 new shares and Pounds 65 for every 100
Micrelec shares.
Meggitt has received irrevocable acceptances from directors holding 35.6 per
cent of Micrelec's shares and undertakings from institutional shareholders
to accept, subject to no higher offer, representing a further 12.2 per cent.
Mr Nigel McCorkell, Meggitt's managing director, said Micrelec's electronics
systems for retail petrol distribution would fit with systems developed by
Triscan, his company's commercial fuel management subsidiary.
Micrelec also had substantial service and maintenance business with the
likes of BP and Shell which was growing and profitable.
Mr McCorkell said Triscan and Micrelec's retail fuel management businesses
would not be merged although some departments, like R&amp;D, would be brought
together.
The market has known for some time that Micrelec would accept sensible
offers and was is believed to have been approached by interested foreign
buyers in January.
It has suffered in the recession from oil companies cutting back on capital
expenditure.
Micrelec estimates that in the year to March 1992 it achieved sales of
Pounds 16.5m and incurred a pre-tax deficit of Pounds 1.7m.
Mr McCorkell said that for the deal to be non-dilutive in 1993, its first
full year, Micrelec would have to make pre-tax profits of Pounds 2m, a
figure he thought was attainable.
Micrelec, which sold its Normand subsidiary in January for Pounds 7m, has
cash balances of Pounds 5m. Mr David Willis, one of the two main
shareholders, will stay on as managing director.
Gearing after the bid is likely to be about 10 per cent, down slightly from
the 12-15 per cent position after the Dollars 53m acquisition in March of
Endevco, the US maker of pressure sensors and other electronic equipment.
The acquisition will bring sales in Meggitt's electronics division to Pounds
60m, still behind its controls and aerospace activities.
</TEXT>
