FT  07 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Interest turnround pushes Stanhope to
Pounds 15.3m loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STANHOPE PROPERTIES, the London office developer which is one third owned by
Olympia &amp; York, the troubled Canadian company, more than halved its pre-tax
losses from Pounds 33.8m to Pounds 15.3m in the six months to December 31.
However, excluding exceptional items, the losses almost doubled from Pounds
8.77m. The deterioration resulted from an swing from interest receivable of
Pounds 6.61m to interest payable of Pounds 7.09m.
This followed an increase in borrowings from Pounds 35m to Pounds 165m and
the waiver of the interest on outstanding shareholder loans to the Rosehaugh
Stanhope Developments joint venture. The share of the losses of associated
undertakings shrank from Pounds 14.7m to Pounds 9.43m, partly as a result of
this waiver.
A charge of Pounds 1.19m resulted from the abortive merger talks with
Rosehaugh, its partner on the Broadgate development in the City, which were
broken off early this year.
'By common consent the property sector is experiencing the most difficult
conditions in living memory,' said the company. 'While there are few, if
any, signs of an early improvement, the anticipated further lowering of
interest rates coupled with increasing economic activity should, in due
course, bring a return of confidence to, and the recovery of, the London
office market.'
Stanhope said that it was actively pursuing a number of low risk partnership
developments in the UK and Europe. It had recently been appointed by British
Rail to act as its partner in a 12-acre mixed use scheme at Oxford Station.
Turnover grew to Pounds 24.3m (Pounds 19.6m), helped by a rise in the rent
roll to Pounds 6.5m (Pounds 4.5m). A subsidiary that specialises in fitting
out offices accounts for 70 per cent of turnover. Administration costs were
cut to Pounds 4.79m (Pounds 5.83m).
Losses per share fell from 20.37p to 9.21p.
