<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Tate &amp; Lyle slips to 'satisfactory' Pounds
92m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POOR WEATHER conditions and pressure on cereal sweetener margins were mainly
to blame for a slight fall in interim profits at Tate &amp; Lyle, from Pounds
94.7m to Pounds 92m pre-tax.
The shares fell 9p to 401p.
Mr Neil Shaw, chairman, predicted a 'satisfactory year in the prevailing
conditions'. He said the six month period, to March 28, had been a good one
in terms of enlarging the group's foundations.
Mr Shaw said that the acquisition last year of Bundaberg in Australia gave
the group a way into the south-east Asian market, and the company had more
than covered its financing costs. In the half-year Tate invested more than
Pounds 30m in central Europe which Mr Shaw said was an important market.
The group has high hopes for two products - Splenda and Stellar  - which are
low calorie alternatives to sugar and fat. Splenda is being sold in Canada
and is awaiting approval from the US authorities, which Mr Shaw hoped would
come this year. A number of competitors had appeared to Stellar and the
build-up in production would be slower than earlier hoped.
Group sales were almost 10 per cent higher at Pounds 1.63bn and operating
profits were up 2.5 per cent to Pounds 115.6m. Associates chipped in Pounds
3.1m (Pounds 1.3m) but higher net interest charges of Pounds 26.7m (Pounds
19.4m) cut the pre-tax figure.
The tax rate was lower at 26 per cent (30 per cent) and Mr Paul Lewis,
finance director, said he expected that rate to apply for the year. Minority
interests took Pounds 10.5m (Pounds 9.6m). Earnings per share were slightly
higher at 13.2p (13.1p) on a fully diluted basis.
The interim dividend is increased by 8.1 per cent to 4p (3.7p).
Trading profits fell in two important divisions, both in the US, with the
impact softened by exchange gains.
The US sugar division saw a fall from Pounds 23.7m to Pounds 17.6m, caused
by poor weather affecting sugar beet which was awaiting processing at
Western Sugar. Profits at Western fell 80 per cent, but were somewhat offset
by a good result from Domino Sugar, based in the eastern US.
Also in the US the cereal sweeteners and starches business saw profits down
from Pounds 34.6m to Pounds 29.9m, with margins cut from 11.9 to 9.5 per
cent, as cool weather and overcapacity affected volumes.
Pre-interest profits from the Canadian sugar business rose 15 per cent to
Pounds 4.7m; in the UK sugar profits were up 6.4 per cent to Pounds 25.1m;
Bundaberg made Pounds 5.3m before financing costs and sugar profits from
elsewhere, such as Europe and Africa, were up 39 per cent at Pounds 8.5m.
The European starch business increased profits by 14 per cent to Pounds
26.2m. Profits from sugar by-products, such as molasses, rose to Pounds
11.3m (Pounds 9.1m). Commodity trading made Pounds 100,000 (loss Pounds
300,000) and other activities, which includes Splenda, lost Pounds 10m
(Pounds 9.7m).
COMMENT
After five years of double-digit earnings growth Tate can be forgiven a
period of consolidation. There is plenty to look forward to in the longer
term if the promise of Splenda and Stellar is realised and Tate wins its
share of the annual growth in the world sugar market. But meanwhile, this
year's profits depend heavily on the weather, and are likely to be a few
million pounds one side or the other of last year's Pounds 234.6m. If they
were unchanged, the lower tax rate would lift earnings a touch, giving a p/e
of about 11.8. The shares are unlikely to do well until there are signs of a
return to growth.
</TEXT>
