<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / The Lex Column: British Gas
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The market was largely unimpressed by yesterday's feisty reminder from Sir
James McKinnon that he is not about to let British Gas alone. But the
regulator was also threatening that the fundamental differences between the
two sides may yet develop from mere niggling into a full-blown monopoly
reference.
Even by its previous standards, Ofgas's challenge on domestic gas prices was
an aggressive and not fully merited swipe. Gas can fairly argue that when it
froze prices ahead of the election, it was working on a much more cloudy
inflation outlook. But that does not help its case while the two sides are
not talking. The threat is not that a price cut would be devastating for
Gas's profits. More worrying for investors is that the burden of regulatory
changes is starting to slow the company down. This could expose a strategic
problem. Gas has been trying to counteract domestic pressure by building an
exploration division and a global supply company. These businesses are
supposed to account for 60 per cent of profits by the end of the decade, but
already the weak oil price augurs badly. If that approach looks like
failing, the long-term progression of Gas's dividend will be in doubt. The
market might find that prospect rather more unnerving than yesterday's
sabre-rattling.
</TEXT>
