<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / The Lex Column: Braving the heights
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The strength of the UK equity market continues to astonish. Since the
election, the FT-SE is up by more than 300 points, or 13 per cent. At the
time of the election result, the more bullish broking houses predicted 3,000
by the year end. The market is half way there already. It only needs another
150 points on the index for the return on equities to match that on cash
between now and the end of the year. Even now, the ratio of gilt yields to
equity yields is only just above two, which puts it at the low end of the
historic range. Over the past 12 months, the UK market has risen only half
as fast as Wall Street. Now that the UK economic recovery, like that of the
US, is tentatively established, can the FT-SE match the Dow by pressing into
record territory?
Part of the difficulty in answering lies in gauging overseas demand. US
buying was reportedly strong yesterday, presumably on the grounds that the
combination of interest rate cuts and a right-of-centre government appeals
to any US fund manager out to diversify away from a possibly overvalued
domestic market. But US investors have proved fickle already this year in
such modish sectors as pharmaceuticals. There is also the risk that UK
finance directors will be lured by these heady levels into cash calls, which
will fall mainly on the UK institutions. Given that the gilt market
recovered only modestly yesterday and that the money market still seems
sceptical about whether Tuesday's rate cut will hold, it may yet prove that
the equity market is more bullish than sober reflection can justify.
</TEXT>
