<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Letter: Prosecution not measure of success
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mrs LYNNE BEAL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I welcome Nigel Wilkins' support (Letters, April 29) for the
introduction of penalties for the late filing of company accounts. However,
he incorrectly equates Companies House compliance effort with the number of
directors prosecuted. We aim to secure compliance with the filing
requirements of the Companies Act rather than to prosecute.
Companies House has an active compliance programme, which includes the issue
of letters and explanatory leaflets, regular roadshows and seminars around
the UK, national advertising campaigns, and a video. Where these measures
fail, we do, of course, prosecute.
But a truer measure of our success is the fact that, currently, 8 per cent
more companies are filed up-to-date than at the same time last year. This
figure is encouraging, but the introduction of late filing penalties should
be seen as an indication that Companies House is determined to improve upon
this figure even further. In this way, we can offer a better service to the
many customers who are entitled to the up-to-date information.
Lynne Beal,
assistant director (compliance),
Companies House,
Crown Way,
Cardiff CP4 3UZ,
Wales
</TEXT>
