<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Arts: Proms 1992 season announced
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Eleven overseas orchestras, seven BBC commissions plus another ten
premieres, works by 104 composers of whom 23 are living and 22 (including
Handel) are British - the statistics of the 1992 Proms came spilling forth
from director John Drummond yesterday.
There will be 66 concerts (all at the Albert Hall) in the 58 eight day
season. It all starts on July 17 with the Princess of Wales in the audience
for a Verdi Requiem and it ends on September 12 with Dame Kiri singing
operatic arias - and 'Rule, Britannia ]'.
Among the highlights are the visits by the Vienna Philharmonic, under both
Abbado and Pierre Boulez, and the St Petersburg Philharmonic also with two
conductors, Jansons and Temirkanov; new works by Richard Rodney Bennett and
John Tavener; plenty of Rossini, including arrangements from his operas by
jazzman Mike Westbrook; and the British premiere of William Walton's suite
Christopher Columbus.
There will be more early music, slightly less opera this season, although
Glyndebourne will bring a semi-staged version of The Queen of Spades. Ticket
prices are only marginally higher than last year but the top price for 55 of
the concerts remains a reasonable Pounds 15.
