<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Arts: The Bacchae - Opera
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
John Buller (b. 1927), whose adaptation of Euripides's Bacchae is the latest
new opera to be presented by English National Opera, is an extraordinary and
peculiarly attractive figure among postwar British composers. He spent much
of his working life outside the world of music, as an architectural
surveyor, and came to it late, driven by personal need.
At least one piece on his short work-list - Proenca (1978), a tautly spun,
richly appealing stretch of orchestral song-setting from medieval Provencal
poetry - has already achieved international circulation. Buller's broad
intellectual interests have fed fertile imaginative inspiration into each
one of his artistic conceptions. The Theatre of Memory, the large orchestral
work first given at the 1981 Proms, may be seen as the direct ancestor of
the new opera in its marriage of ancient Greek theories of memory and
Renaissance conventions of drama.
Buller's insistence on the original ancient Greek words for his ENO Bacchae
 -already widely publicised  - should be seen not as a dotty elitist quirk,
but as consistent with an intense artistic response to the 'feel' of
language (as shown in Proenca), and with an out-of-time approach to
composition. It is no surprise to learn, from an interview in the programme,
that previously he had had no desire to write an opera at all, and that the
subject of his Bacchae was chosen as a sort of 'just response' to Henze's
Bassarids - a very different Euripides opera - as also mounted (in 1978) by
ENO.
For this, as shown at Tuesday's opening performance, is by no means a
straightforward new Bacchae opera to add to the 20th-century list. (Last
year Andrew Porter reported on the Stockholm premiere of Daniel Bortz's
Backanterna, produced by Ingmar Bergman, and in 1990 Andrew Clark described
the 1990 Bielefeld revival of Egon Wellesz's 1931 Bakchantinnen.) My gut
reaction, indeed, is that it is not really an opera at all but, rather, a
type of enacted Bacchae frieze, expertly arrayed, which may well come to be
more fittingly displayed in concert-hall circumstances.
It's hard to imagine a more confidently composed frieze. Buller, whose only
imposition on the play has been to condense it into an unbroken 100-minute
structure, avoids entirely the faults of inexperience - overscoring,
over-extension of material, uncertainties of pacing and word-setting - that
usually stamp first stage-works. The beguiling sound-world of this Bacchae
is its most memorable achievement: Lutoslawski-like in absolute cleanliness
of line, beautifully spaced and contrasted for both voices and instruments,
never clotted or uncertain of purpose or contour.
The work is planned in the form of 17 linked scenes, and marked out in
'realms' of distinct atmospheric texture - by, for example, Dionysus's
liquidly trickling celesta and woodwind, Pentheus's fractious brass consort,
or the frequent unisons and snapping intervallic leaps of the female chorus.
The main characters have their particular vocal styles; Dionysus and
Pentheus are both high tenors differently treated (Dionysus, in addition, is
the only character to use English, when speaking as a god rather than to the
other personages on stage).
Exotic, rather Roussel-like streams of modal harmony, motivic influences
from ancient Greek scales and a fastidious richness of colouristic detail
all aid in supplying the score with its highly individual patina. The
treatment of the play is coolly sophisticated, with absolutely none of the
Expressionist gesture-thrusting and Grand Opera noise-making that other
20th-century composers have thought fit for Greek subjects.
What to my mind this Bacchae lacks is any of the unrepeatable combustion of
dramatic subject and music that is the root characteristic of many different
kinds of opera. The effect of listening to an opera in a dead language is,
as we know from Stravinsky's 'opera-oratorio' Oedipus rex, to repose fullest
concentration upon the dramatic workings of the music. (The libretto
promises more interventions from a narrator than on Tuesday we were given.)
In this case, I felt that the result was to heighten awareness of an
oversimplification of the dramatic subject. With its long scenes built upon
immobile pedal points and its characterisation devoid of psychological
perspective, this seems to me a static Bacchae, whose presentation in a
theatre adds nothing 'kinetic' to my understanding of it, or of the
Euripides play.
By this I mean disrespect neither to the fine, confident musical realisation
under Martin Andre nor to the grippingly intelligent, economical ENO staging
by Julia Hollander in Hildegard Bechtler's rough-hewn angled-box set and
Nicky Gillibrand's bold costumes. The producer has devised a sinuous,
startlingly effective kind of sculptural body-language, derived from Indian
dance, which Dionysus and the Bacchantes employ to contrast with the bans.
This inspires Thomas Randle (Dionysus) to give a sensational performance,
glamorously embodied and lustrously sung, that is alone worth the ticket
price. Sarah Walker, whose mezzo Agave enters the scene only at the
seven-eighth point, sings with moving eloquence; the less obviously grateful
roles taken by respectively Graeme Matheson-Bruce, Gregory Yurisich and
Richard Van Allan with notable authority, and the singing of the nine-strong
female ensemble is thrilling.
London Coliseum (071-836-3161): in repertory until May 28
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21
</PAGE>
