<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / People: Bringing intelligence to bear on buildings
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Doug Oughton, a director of Oscar Faber Consulting Engineers, is the first
chairman of the European Intelligent Building Group, which spreads the
message across the continent about the merits of what is termed
'intelligence' in building design and construction.
The EIBG grew out of the Intelligent Building Group, a co-operative that
claims to have gained considerable momentum in recent years. It counts among
its members consultant engineers such as Oscar Faber, architects including
DEGW, Lloyd's of London as a 'user', a selection of suppliers to the
building trade and a coterie of academics. The first European members in the
expanded operation include Legrand, the French electrical supplies
manufacturer.
Oughton, who is well known in the industry and a long-serving fellow of the
Chartered Institute of Building Services Engineers, specialises in energy
conservation at Oscar Faber. He will be chairman of EIBG for a year.
While no-one can quite agree on a definition of exactly what constitutes the
intelligent building, Oughton stresses that it is more than state-of-the-art
technology. 'It is rather a case of looking at everything that improves the
productivity of the workplace.' The Lloyd's representative cites for
instance the dividends paid by flexibility - as when Lloyd's immediately
offered a workable home to the Baltic Exchange after the latter's City
premises were destroyed by the recent IRA bomb.
DEGW has just completed a 1,100 page study devoted to intelligent buildings
in Europe. While this started off as an IBG idea the group did not then have
the resources to effect it itself. Now it would, says Oughton, who says such
studies are an important way of influencing consultants.
</TEXT>
