<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Management (Marketing and Advertising): Desert island discs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's commercial television viewers may be surprised to see a 30-second
advertisement promoting the services of Andersen Consulting sandwiched
between promotions for instant coffee and cars.
In the advertisement, a man stranded on a desert island finds a wooden crate
containing a desktop computer. The castaway ingeniously constructs a raft
from the crate and paddles off towards the horizon - using the computer
keyboard as an oar.
The message - echoed in newsprint and poster adverts featuring the slogan
'metamorphosis in a world of change' - is that Andersen Consulting can help
its clients profit from change.
The campaign is evidence of increasing competition among management
consultants, particularly in technology, which is attracting not just the
big management consultants, but also computer hardware and systems
companies.
Although similar marketing campaigns by service companies are familiar in
the US, they are only just catching on in Europe.
However, most of Andersen's competitors are dubious about the value of
television advertising, which they argue can be useful to promote knowledge
of a firm's name, but is ineffective in generating new business.
Keith Burgess, Andersen's UK managing partner, says the Pounds 1m-plus
mass-media campaign is aimed at raising general awareness of Andersen
Consulting. 'We want people to know we are not just another (consultancy)
arm of an accounting firm,' he says.
Because the firm's consultancy work in the public and private sectors
directly affects thousands of workers, Burgess also hopes the campaign will
convey 'our personality' to a wide audience.
One of Andersen's press advertisement juxtaposes the artist Jackson
Pollock's style of 'abstract expressionism' with the 'realism' of Roy
Lichtenstein in order to show how the complex abstract can be transformed
into the tangible.
Burgess is delighted with the 'metamorphosis theme' which he says 'gets
across what we are trying to do with our clients'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
