<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Management (Marketing and Advertising): Turning to
television for the power and the glory - How a Scottish electricity group is
planning to broadcast its message to shareholders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ian Preston, chief executive of the recently-privatised Scottish Power, is
built with the solidity of one of his power stations.
He does not look the sort of man who throws money around lightly. 'Prudent
is the word,' he says.
Yet the practical Preston has recently been spending time in the media
village of London's Soho discussing new ways of getting his message across.
In July, Scottish Power will become the first user of The Business Channel,
which will use BBC television transmitters in the early hours of the morning
to broadcast corporate meetings.
A half-hour edited version of Scottish Power's 1992 annual general meeting
on July 29 will be broadcast at 5.30 the next morning. And although the
programme may catch a few early risers, the main hope is that people will
record it and watch it later.
Scottish Power's agm is not going to make much of a splash in the ratings
but Preston hopes it might help to solve a rather tricky problem - how to
communicate with his 900,000 shareholders.
The company - the first big privatisation in Scotland  - has shareholders
all over the UK. Although some of the original shareholders are likely to
sell, Preston believes his permanent roster is likely to be around 750,000.
Preston is afraid that many of the company's letters or brochures 'arrive
with the junk mail and many get the same kind of treatment'. He was
initially sceptical about The Business Channel, run as a joint venture
between a new company, BMH Communications, and BBC Select, the subscription
television arm of the Corporation.
BMH was set up by Bryan Hall, the film producer who believes that eventually
it could be broadcasting up to 250 hours a year on both BBC 1 and BBC 2
between 2am and 6am.
'I think we have all warmed to the idea as we began to think what the pluses
are in communicating with both shareholders and staff,' said Preston.
The half-hour programme will cost Scottish Power Pounds 30,000, not
including production costs, but for that they will be able to show an
eight-minute corporate video as well as the highlights of the meeting all
over the UK, albeit it an unearthly hour.
Preston is determined that the programme will be 'a fair representation of
what takes place. Otherwise there is no point in it'.
If there is a riot at the agm in Glasgow that will be shown too.
The programme will be listed in both the Radio Times and TV Times but
Scottish Power will also publicise its experiment in corporate
communications to try to make sure as many shareholders set their video
recorders as possible.
BMH says it is talking to a number of large companies about using the new
channel. Under the agreement with the BBC, it is possible to broadcast any
valid public meeting whether annual or extraordinary or part of a campaign
to fight-off a predator.
Straight advertising of products is not allowed but a meeting to launch a
new range of products or fashions to buyers could be broadcast on The
Business Channel using BBC transmitters.
Preston views his move into national television very much as an experiment
and will be watching carefully to see what kind of audience and reaction he
gets to Scottish Power: The AGM.
Before he hands out another Pounds 30,000, the Scottish Power chief
executive will want to be sure the message was spread a bit more widely than
at his first agm last year when the company catered for an audience of 6,000
and actually got 600.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9616</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAA4FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Business Law: Tangled skein of tax adjustments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOSEPH FLOM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The differing legal systems and currency fluctuations of nations create
burdens on cross-border investment and commerce. These discrepancies often
cause the greatest inefficiencies when they involve the taxation of
international business transactions.
Most developed countries have long recognised the seriousness of tax
inefficiencies and have adopted a network of bilateral tax treaties, based
on models developed by the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and
Development, which are intended to reduce the potential for double taxation
of income from cross-border transactions.
The US has been a leader in this effort but, over the past several years,
has pursued a course that, if not properly contained, has the potential
fundamentally to undermine these arrangements.
The US Internal Revenue Service has become increasingly concerned that many
foreign-owned US companies are systematically under-allocating the portion
of their worldwide income that should properly be attributable to sales and
other activities in the US.
The source of this IRS concern is data gathered in the late 1980s which tend
to establish that foreign-controlled US corporations earn a substantially
lower rate of return in the US than do US-controlled companies.
IRS data indicate that while US-controlled corporations had a ratio of
taxable income to assets ranging from 1.6 per cent to 1.9 per cent during
the period 1983-87, the ratio for foreign-owned US corporations ranged from
minus 0.2 per cent to plus 0.8 per cent.
There are plausible explanations for statistical discrepancies: the fact
that many foreign-owned US companies were acquired within the past decade
and thus have relatively high book asset values; that foreign investors may
be willing to accept a lower return to gain market share in the US; and so
on. But US Treasury and academic economists have not been able to establish
to their satisfaction a statistical basis for any alternative explanations
to the under-allocation of worldwide income to the US.
Responding in part to this data, the IRS has assigned a large part of its
audit and legal staff to foreign-owned US company cases. These auditors are
often aggressive, and suspicious of the audited taxpayer. This has resulted
in cases that are beginning to overload IRS administrative appeals channels
and the US Tax Court.
The IRS readily admits that dealing with these cases through litigation is
inefficient and prefers to resolve them through government-to-government
negotiations under the so-called 'competent authority' provisions of various
bilateral US tax treaties.
The average competent authority case requires two to four years to be
resolved. Because resolution requires the voluntary agreement of both
governments and the taxpayer, success is unlikely unless the foreign
government is willing to refund a portion of any tax payments made to it by
the parent multinational as an offset to the US adjustment.
The US and Japan, for example, agreed in the late 1980s to competent
authority settlements resulting in Japanese refund payments for Toyota,
Nissan and Honda that have been reported to total hundreds of millions of
dollars for each company. Since that experience, Japan's National Tax
Administration has been reluctant to accommodate further US adjustments.
It is thus difficult to see how voluntary competent authority proceedings
are likely to resolve the flood of IRS-initiated adjustments.
It may not be long before other governments decide to follow the IRS example
and initiate their own adjustments against US-based multinationals. The
revenue stakes are potentially enormous. The techniques developed by the IRS
to analyse the activities of foreign-based multinationals can readily be
applied by foreign governments to US-based companies. Given that US tax
rates are generally lower than those of other leading industrial countries,
it is possible that any corporate under-allocation of income to non-resident
jurisdiction applies outside as well as inside the US.
The problem results in part from the internationally agreed tax rules for
related party cross-border transactions, which were largely developed in the
1960s. These rules establish the standard of 'arm's length' dealings between
related parties.
The quest is to determine what unrelated parties dealing with each other at
arm's length would have charged for the relevant goods, services or use of
intangibles. Finding persuasive evidence of what such unrelated parties
would have charged in similar circumstances is often impossible. Many
industries, such as cars, electronics and pharmaceuticals, are dominated by
integrated companies where there are few transactions between unrelated
parties at the same level of trade.
Moreover, multinational related parties enter into specific arrangements
that unrelated parties are often unwilling or unable to obtain - such as
exclusive supply and purchase arrangements or long-term licences of existing
and future technology.
Finally, the efficiencies and long-term perspective of many integrated
multinational corporations often make their expectations of returns in
specific markets at any given time much different from those of an
independent company doing business only in a few geographic markets.
For these reasons, no third-party transaction prices or formula for
determining prices can be identified as correct for any particular
multinational. Instead, a broad range of prices is likely to command nearly
equal merit, even though the price chosen within that range has a
substantial impact on the allocation of income between taxing jurisdictions.
In this setting, IRS auditors can identify a set of reasonably correct
prices that create a substantial allocation of income to the US during the
years under audit. Similarly, in a wide variety of cases, other governments
can no doubt identify adjustments that create a substantial income
re-allocation to their country. Thus new solutions to income allocation
disputes are required.
One possible approach has recently been implemented on a trial basis by the
IRS. It is a procedure for advance pricing agreements (called APAs) among
the IRS, relevant foreign governments and a specific multinational taxpayer.
Each agreement would apply for three or more years subject to further
renewal. It can cover the pricing of specific transactions involving goods,
services or intangibles or can establish a more global allocation of income
generally between two or more related entities.
The IRS has discussed this procedure with various foreign governments and
has found a willingness to entertain negotiations for specific agreements
from Australia, Canada, Germany and the UK, among others. The first
agreement has recently been completed, involving a US-based manufacturer and
its sales affiliate resident in Australia.
This APA procedure holds out much hope as a prototype for avoiding the
spread of inter-company pricing controversies. It is customised to each
taxpayer's circumstances, permitting the creation of specific formulas for
pricing and income allocation that meet realistic expectation of the revenue
authorities of each country.
Because any agreement is achieved in advance of the years in question, the
APA procedure resolves a problem with the current system: the fact that
governments are reluctant to part with revenues that have already been
collected.
Moreover, if the procedure is applied to a large enough group of taxpayers,
a series of informal guidelines may evolve that can be applied on a broader
industry or other basis. Over time, elements of agreed standards might be
developed to apply even to taxpayers not choosing to participate in an APA
procedure.
Any solution to current problems will only work if foreign governments
perceive that their interests are served as well. If that perception is
developed through negotiation, a source of potentially serious tax barriers
to cross-border commerce can be eliminated.
The author is the senior partner of the New York based international law
firm of Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &amp; Flom.
</TEXT>
