<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Engineers urge better technology teaching
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN 'EIGHT-POINT plan' to promote technology teaching in schools was put
forward yesterday by the Engineering Council.
The plan calls for a practical technology curriculum, based on the design
and manufacture of products and systems. It is written by Professor Alan
Smithers and Dr Pamela Robinson of Manchester University's education
department.
They say technology is poorly taught in schools in spite of its inclusion as
a core subject in the national curriculum. It is mainly concerned with
generalised problem solving without specific knowledge or practical
application.
'Technology lacks an identity in the national curriculum,' they say. 'But
Britain is the first country to make technology part of the compulsory
curriculum for all pupils aged five to 16 . . . and some false starts are
perhaps inevitable.'
The report points to the difficulty experienced in devising suitable
technology assignments as part of the compulsory tests being introduced for
14-year-olds.
Mr Denis Filer, director general of the Engineering Council, told a press
conference that the plan had to be implemented if school technology 'is to
be given credibility and respect among the community at large and with
industry'.
Technology in the National Curriculum, A. Smithers &amp; P. Robinson.
Engineering Council, 10 Maltravers St, London WC2R 3ER. Free.
</TEXT>
