<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Queen's Speech: Freeing the market for milk - Agricultural
marketing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE drawn-out process of bringing to a close the Milk Marketing Board's
60-year-old monopoly right to buy milk appears to be gathering pace.
The announcement in the Queen's Speech that legislation would 'be introduced
to promote improvements in agricultural marketing' is mainly aimed at the
reform of the MMB - a long-term aim of the government.
Shortly after the election last month, and only a few days before the
government's Easter deadline, the MMB submitted to the Agriculture Ministry
its plans to turn itself into a single voluntary co-operative with pooled
prices. The ministry said the legislation would be intended to help the
MMB's move 'to a new structure better able to protect the interests of
producers and consumers in the European single market.'
The ministry has not yet made a formal response to the plans, which will
also have to be approved by the European Commission.
The MMB, which has put up stiff resistance to reforming itself, was debating
the reforms for two years. The plans include the spinning off of Dairy
Crest, its wholly owned subsidiary with a 25 per cent share of the UK's
manufactured dairy products market.
Yesterday Mr Bob Steven, MMB chairman, said: 'In changing a structure that
has existed for nearly 60 years, future legislation must seek to preserve as
many benefits of the current system as possible.' It must give farmers and
dairy companies 'a fair opportunity to adapt their businesses to changed
circumstances,' he added.
Legislation is also being introduced to end government guarantees for the
Potato Marketing Board and British Wool Marketing Board intervention
schemes. The government has not spent any money on the potato scheme since
1984, but the ministry said yesterday that the wool scheme had cost Pounds
40m last year.
However, the wool board said yesterday it was well prepared for the end of
the wool scheme, as the government first announced its intention to reform
it at the opening of the previous Parliament.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
