<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Queen's Speech (Analysis): Push for personal provision -
Pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S legislative programme heralded few surprises on the
pensions front. Indeed, it may have been more notable for what it did not
say about pensions than what it did.
The speech made no reference to pension law reform - an issue that had been
rising on the political agenda since the disappearance of more than Pounds
400m from pension funds controlled by the late Mr Robert Maxwell.
Instead, it focused exclusively on personal pensions. As foreshadowed in
February by the then social security minister, Mr Tony Newton, the
government has pledged to maintain the increase in personal pensions which
its tax breaks first inspired in 1988. The 2 per cent incentive payment to
those opting out of the government's State Earnings Related Pension Scheme,
which expires in April 1993, will be replaced by a more modest rebate of 1
per cent on tax payments. Only those over the age of 30 - roughly 40 per
cent of the nation's 4.6m personal pension holders  - will benefit from the
new rebate.
The total cost of the new rebate, at Pounds 175m per year, is considerably
below the estimated Pounds 685m annual cost of the current pension incentive
payment.
The rebate will apply to the national insurance payments of individuals
between the lower and upper wage bands (currently between Pounds 54 and
Pounds 405 a week). At best, this will cut an individual's payments by
Pounds 182.52 per year under the current tax structure.
The Department of Social Security says the new lower tax incentive is
intended to run for 'at least three years', suggesting that no more efforts
to tinker with private social security schemes are envisaged.
The new 1 per cent incentive payment has angered occupational pension
schemes, the members of which will not benefit from it. The National
Association of Pension Funds, the trade body representing those schemes, has
condemned the policy, saying it unfairly promotes private pensions at the
expense of employer-sponsored plans.
</TEXT>
