<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Japan announces big increase in payments surplus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S current account surplus for March more than trebled to Dollars
13.58bn (Pounds 7.6bn), bringing the surplus for the 1991 fiscal year to
Dollars 90bn, a 167 per cent increase and a likely source of trade friction
with Washington.
The leap in the surplus, which was not far below the peak of Dollars 94bn in
1986, included a record surplus of Dollars 113bn in the trade account, and
is expected to prompt renewed international demands that Japan stimulate a
slowing domestic economy.
Balance of payment figures released by the finance ministry also showed the
long-term capital account had a surplus of Dollars 40bn for fiscal 1991, a
turnaround from a deficit of Dollars 16.8bn in the previous year and the
first surplus since 1980.
The surplus followed a sharp increase in foreign net purchases of Japanese
securities, which rose from Dollars 60bn in 1990 to Dollars 101bn, and a
smaller rise in Japanese net purchases of foreign securities, up from
Dollars 48.8bn to Dollars 61bn.
Bonds were Japanese investors' main target, as net purchases of foreign
stocks fell from Dollars 847m to only Dollars 118m, while foreign capital
was used to purchase a net Dollars 36.77bn in Japanese stocks, up from
Dollars 15.92bn in fiscal 1990.
Finance ministry officials said the current account surplus had peaked, and
blamed the surge in March surplus on the payment of Japan's Dollars 9bn
contribution to the Gulf War effort in the same month last year. But the
government fears that the large total for Japan's 1991 fiscal year, which
runs to the end of March 1992, will be an easy target for foreign criticism
of Japanese trade and fiscal policies.
Mr Matthew Berlow, economist at Credit Lyonnais Securities (Japan), said
that the large current account surplus, in theory, should have been
accompanied by an outflow of capital from Japan, but foreigners' purchases
of Japanese securities in recent months had upset the trend.
'In the longer term, these figures must even out. There has been a lot of
fears about Japanese pulling money out, but they are still buying foreign
securities. We will have to see what happens in April,' Mr Berlow said.
Japanese direct investment in 1991 was Dollars 23.6bn, down from Dollars
44.9bn, showing the effects of tougher financial conditions at home and the
international recession. Foreign direct investment in Japan, as recorded by
the ministry, doubled from a year earlier but was still a mere Dollars
2.2bn.
The Japanese deficit in invisible trade, including tourism, fell 14.5 per
cent from 1990 to Dollars 19.2bn, following an increase in transfers to
Japan of investment income. In the overall balance of payments, the surplus
soared from Dollars 961m in 1990 to Dollars 114bn.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9629</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAARFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Hekmatyar halts assault on Kabul
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE LEVINE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KABUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RADICAL Mujahideen leader Gulbuddin Hekmatyar halted his assault on Kabul
yesterday so that peace talks could be held with his rivals in the new
Mujahideen government.
Mr Hekmatyar's five-man delegation demanded, among other things, that
President Sigbutulla Mojaddedi's powers to select cabinet ministers be
eliminated.
He also wants an 8,000-man Uzbek militia backing his chief rival, defence
minister Ahmad Shah Massoud, to leave the capital region.
Mr Massoud's chief deputy, Mr Abdur Rahaman, said in an interview that the
ruling 51-member council would negotiate with Mr Hekmatyar, 'but one-way
demands are not reasonable. He should accept the decisions of the council.'
Mr Masoud's political leader, Mr Berhanuddin Rabbanni, who will assume the
nation's presidency in six weeks, is expected to meet Mr Hekmatyar on the
outskirts of Kabul today.
The peace talks are expected to lead to Mr Hekmatyar's admission to the
interim government in some form.
Although Mr Hekmatyar had appeared to isolate himself from nearly all major
Mujahideen leaders by continuing to fight despite Kabul's fall two weeks
ago, it has become clear that his rivals are not ready to sever ties with
him.
This means that a member of Mr Hekmatyar's organisation, Hezb-i-Islami, will
probably assume the post of prime minister. Mr Hekmatyar has nominated one
of his northern commanders, Ustad Fareed, to take the position, and he seems
to have been accepted by most of the rebel factions participating in the
government.
Analysts believe Mr Massoud is reconciled to his bitter enemy joining the
government, but that he would like to delay the move as long as possible.
'Masoud doesn't want to annihilate Hekmatyar. Basically his strategy is to
weaken him sufficiently, then let him join the government,' said an Asian
diplomat.
Mr Hekmatyar, 39, is believed to have huge stockpiles of weapons from his 14
years as the chief recipient of Dollars 9bn (Pounds 5bn) in US aid to the
Mujahideen. A gifted organiser and orator with fierce determination, Mr
Hekmatyar has been able to stall and bully his way into powerful positions
throughout the war.
Meanwhile, Mr Abdul Wakil, the deposed regime's foreign minister, was said
to have fled to Tashkent. Mr Wakil became the face of the government after
ex-president Najibullah went into hiding.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9630</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAAQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Australia cuts interest rates again
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Reserve Bank of Australia yesterday cut official interest rates for the
12th time since 1990, ignoring signs that recovery from 18 months of
economic stagnation or decline is already under way.
The Bank announced a cut of one percentage point in official cash rates to
6.5 per cent, the lowest since the mid-1970s. Rates have now been cut by
11.5 percentage points since peaking at 18 per cent in January 1990.
Mr Bernie Fraser, the reserve bank governor, said the cut was justified by
zero growth in the consumer price index in the three months to the end of
March. Inflation is currently 1.7 per cent a year.
Mr Fraser said the economic recovery was uneven, and forecast that excess
capacity would restrain upward pressure on prices. 'A reduction in rates
will help business cash flow, and provide some encouragement (to companies)
to undertake new investments,' he said.
Mr John Dawkins, the federal Treasurer (finance minister), said inflation
expectations were on 'a downward trend,' and forecast that inflation would
average less than 2 per cent for the remainder of 1992.
Mr Dawkins said the outlook for inflation would be 'very important for the
future stance of monetary policy.' He said the government 'will stand ready
to increase rates if circumstances require.'
