FT  07 MAY 92 / Economic growth to top European finance ministers' talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK BLUM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LISBON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ECONOMIC growth in Europe is likely to top the agenda at this weekend's
informal meeting of European Community finance ministers in Oporto, northern
Portugal.
High European interest rates, rising public sector indebtedness, and
sluggish growth prospects prompted Mr Pierre Beregovoy, the French prime
minister, to write to his EC counterparts urging a high level discussion on
promoting EC growth.
Mr Jorge Braga de Macedo, Portugal's finance minister, yesterday said that
the ministers would seek concerted action through a Community-wide
'non-inflationary growth policy'. He also said that the ministers would
examine several structural impediments to European growth and review
concerted means of eliminating these obstacles.
Ministers are expected to examine developments towards the single market and
ways to promote competition in the non-tradeable goods sector, including
services, distribution and the labour and capital markets. 'There is scope
for initiatives in these areas,' Mr Braga de Macedo said.
A paper from the Committee of Central Bank governors on stage two of
European Monetary Union, due to start in January 1994, will attempt to
define some of the steps involved. The thorny issue of choosing a site for
the European Monetary Institute (EMI), which would be converted into a
European central bank by 1999 at the latest, is expected to be raised
separately.
Other topics include requests by non-EC countries for their currencies to be
linked formally to the exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary
System.
Ministers are also expected to discuss broadening EC economic assistance to
all the republics of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), as well
as the possible extension of European Investment Bank activities to Latin
America.
Discussion of the Community's 1993-97 budget is expected to focus on
improving budgetary discipline and transparency by raising efficiency and
reducing bureaucracy.
'Some (Community) procedures are far too slow, and we want to find ways to
ensure that taxpayers' money is not wasted,' Mr Braga de Macedo said.
</TEXT>
