<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / French assembly split on Maastricht
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN DAVIDSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE French debate on ratifying the Maastricht Treaty on European Union
heated up yesterday after the French national assembly voted down two
procedural attempts to have the whole exercise thrown out as being
unconstitutional.
Both these fundamentally anti-Maastricht moves, one from the Gaullist
right-wing and one from the communists, were rejected by wide margins.
The motion tabled by Mr Philippe Seguin, a standard-bearer of the
nationalist wing of the Gaullist Party, was defeated by 396 to 101; while
the communist motion was defeated by 411 to 54.
The votes against the Maastricht Treaty were much larger than the government
had been expecting, and suggest that the necessary constitutional reform and
ratification of the Treaty could after all turn out to be closely-run.
As it is, the government has already been forced to give ground to
opposition protests that it tried to ram through the constitutional revision
at unreasonable speed during the preliminary committee stage.
As a result the full national assembly debate, which was to have been
concluded tonight, is being extended with an additional day's discussion
next Tuesday, and will then be wound up with a vote.
But if the size of the two anti-Maastricht votes in the national assembly is
moderately worrying for the Socialist government, it is deeply disturbing
for the right-wing Gaullist party, because it has again opened up the deep
split over the issue of Europe which has traditionally run right down the
middle of the party.
Before the debate, Mr Jacques Chirac, the leader of the Gaullists, attempted
a compromise with tepid support for the Treaty and modest criticism of the
constitutional revision, which he hoped would satisfy both the pro- and
anti-Europeans in the party.
But his attempt to forge a facade of unity in the party has now been blown
apart by the fiercest debate on France's European destiny since the Treaty
of Rome in 1957. Nearly half the Gaullist contingent in the national
assembly (58 out of 126 members) voted for the Seguin motion, and 16
Gaullists even voted for the communist motion.
Some commentators play down the operational significance of yesterday's
votes. The Gaullists knew the anti-European motions would be defeated, so
they could afford a display of anti-European and anti-government ill-temper;
but next Tuesday the more prudent members may fall back into line behind the
leadership.
As a potential candidate in the next presidential elections, Mr Chirac will
find it more difficult to pose as a constructive if prudent European
statesman when nearly half his parliamentary party appears implacably
opposed to the whole enterprise.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9642</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAAEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Brussels draft budget shows money to spare: Main saving to
come on farm subsidies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission yesterday presented its 1993 draft budget which at
first sight shows the EC has money to spare, thereby undermining its own
controversial plan to increase Community revenue 35 per cent by 1997.
The full 'appropriations' budget would rise from Ecu66.6bn (Pounds 46.62bn)
this year to Ecu67.3bn in 1993, a rise of only 1.1 per cent, against average
spending rises in the member states of 7 per cent. This compares with an
11.3 per cent rise in last year's EC budget and a 19 per cent increase the
year before.
Actual spending this year is forecast at Ecu63.1bn, and Ecu64.3bn next year.
This means that spending in 1992 is below target and that the Commission is
in real terms pitching next year's target below this year's likely outcome.
The EC's revenue ceiling is equivalent to 1.2 per cent of Community gross
national product. This year's forecast outcome would be well within the
ceiling at 1.11 per cent, whereas next year's target would be 1.1 per cent.
Mr Jacques Delors, the Commission president, however, still wants to raise
the revenue base to 1.35 per cent of GNP by 1997, under its new five-year
finance plan.
Net contributors to the budget, led by Germany and the UK, will see the
draft budget as confirming their argument that the revenue base should not
be raised that high because there is enough 'headroom' under the existing
ceiling to accommodate EC spending ambitions.
These ambitions are reflected in the planned 19 per cent rise in regional
spending, from Ecu18.6bn this year to Ecu22.1bn next. This includes Ecu1.6bn
for the 'cohesion fund' to help poorer member states catch up with average
EC living standards. Spending on external aid and foreign policy, and on
research, rises 13 per cent, from Ecu3.6bn to Ecu4.1bn, and from Ecu2.5bn to
Ecu2.8bn respectively.
These priorities and the cohesion fund were agreed at December's Maastricht
summit, but the only attempt to attach sums to them is the so-called 'Delors
II' five-year finance plan which is likely to be whittled down by member
states.
The main saving for 1993 is on farm spending, forecast to drop from
Ecu35.3bn to Ecu32.1bn - the first time since the EC was founded that
agriculture has absorbed less than half the budget. This estimate is based
on current world prices and the strength of the dollar, and also
incorporates modest savings from the Commission's farm reform plan which has
yet to be agreed. But this picture could easily change.
Lower farm spending and more 'cohesion' finance are also likely to increase
pressure on the UK to give up some of the budget rebate it won from 1985,
conceded because it did relatively badly out of a bigger agriculture budget.
Germany, by far the largest net contributor, intends to press for a
reduction of this Ecu2bn rebate, and Mr Delors on Tuesday told Socialist
Euro-MPs that 'consideration of the British situation could be different
from in the past'.
Commission budget officials said yesterday they would recommend whether to
'continue, modify or abolish' the rebate later this month.
</TEXT>
