<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / US calls on CSCE to exclude Serbia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US and other western countries yesterday stepped up the pressure on
Serbia by refusing to recognise it as the legal successor of the former
Yugoslavia, and calling for its exclusion from the Conference on Security
and Co-operation in Europe (CSCE)
The moves to isolate Serbia - and Montenegro, its tiny ally - came as CSCE
members met in Helsinki to discuss the civil war in the independent republic
of Bosnia-Hercegovina and as European Community officials tried to
consolidate the latest ceasefire there.
Mr Haris Silajdzic, Bosnia's foreign minister, repeated his plea at the CSCE
meeting for some form of military intervention from the international
community. But several west European countries were sceptical about
intervening.
Growing international criticism of Serbia coincided with the reconvening of
the EC peace conference in Brussels. Although Mr Alija Izetbegovic, the
president of Bosnia-Hercegovina, remained in Sarajevo, the talks were
attended by President Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia and President Franjo
Tudjman of Croatia, who over the past year have held secret negotiations on
dividing Bosnia.
The EC-brokered ceasefire was agreed on Tuesday just hours after Mr Marrack
Goulding, the United Nations special envoy, arrived in Sarajevo to assess
whether any UN peace-keeping forces would be sent. Mr Goulding, whose convoy
came under fire last Tuesday, was yesterday again attacked. Radio Sarajevo
said a bullet hit the envoy's car.
In other parts of the republic, there were reports of heavy fighting.
Radio Sarajevo said Mostar, southern Bosnia, was pounded by some 500
grenades. Radio Belgrade reported fresh clashes around Zvornik, eastern
Bosnia, one of eight mainly Moslem towns seized by Serb irregulars on or
near the River Drina, Bosnia's eastern frontier with Serbia.
