<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Angry SPD threatens to boycott budget crisis talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GERMANY'S Social Democratic opposition yesterday threatened to boycott
cross-party talks on the country's budget crisis in protest at the
government's plans for drastic cuts in unemployment benefits and job
creation schemes.
The hostile response to the first government proposals for long-term budget
austerity was fuelled by an equally angry reaction at the Federal Labour
Office, which declared that any large-scale savings would only increase the
numbers of fully unemployed - above all in east Germany.
The plan put forward by Mr Theo Waigel, the finance minister, would curb
growth in government spending to a bare 2.5 per cent per year until 1996,
and would abolish any central subsidy for the Labour Office, currently
standing at some DM5bn (Pounds 1.7bn). Spending by the states and local
authorities would be kept to a 3 per cent annual growth rate.
Mr Waigel's aim is to cut his central government budget deficit, a factor
behind the country's current high interest rates, from DM45bn this year to
DM25bn by 1995.
The plan yesterday split the German political and economic establishments on
predictable lines, winning solid support from the Chamber of Trade and
Industry and the ruling coalition partners, and outright hostility from the
Social Democrats (SPD) and the trade union federation (DGB).
Both Mr Bjorn Engholm, the SPD leader, and Mr Hans-Ulrich Klose, the Bonn
parliamentary group leader, called into question their planned talks with
the government on May 27.
Mr Klose said the talks would be pointless on the basis of the 'sloppy and
socially unjust' proposal put forward by the finance minister.
The most disturbing response for Mr Waigel, however, was the reaction of the
Federal Labour Office's conservative president, Mr Heinrich Franke, who
suggested that substantial savings in training and job creation schemes
would simply boost outright unemployment in the east, without any
significant budget saving.
</TEXT>
