FT  06 MAY 92 / International Company News: US media boss predicts recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   New York
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A RECOVERY in earnings in the second half of 1992 was forecast yesterday by
Mr Daniel Burke, president and chief executive of Capital Cities/ABC, the US
television and newspapers group.
Mr Burke, speaking at the annual shareholders's meeting in New York, said
the second-half results would benefit from an improvement in local and
national advertising demand in the broadcasting division. The company's
shares reacted with a rise of dollars 7 3/4 to dollars 448.
'We cannot make predictions beyond that for the balance of the year,
although we expect the company's expense growth to be modest,' Mr Burke
explained.
The media group's 1991 net income declined by 28.1 per cent to dollars
343.5m, on revenues of dollars 5.4bn.
In the first quarter of 1992 net profits at Capital Cities/ABC plunged by 45
per cent, to dollars 58.6m, on unchanged revenues of dollars 1.26bn.
Mr Burke promised that ABC would remain 'a player of consequence' in the
global television market, having established partnerships in seven
international media-based ventures to date.
In the US, ABC Television ended the 1991-92 prime time season in last place,
just behind NBC. 'While I live for the day I can report to you that the
network ranked first or second, I would rather that it made a respectable
profit,' Mr Burke told shareholders.
He noted that the broadcasting division had earned dollars 669.7m of
operating profit last year.
Mr Burke said while Capital Cities was considering acquisitions, it might be
'entering a period where internally developed businesses make more sense for
us'.
He cited several internally generated ventures such as new magazine and
fashion shows that have cost the company dollars 42m pre-tax in start-up
expenses.
</TEXT>
