FT  06 MAY 92 / Usdaw to fight Sunday law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   Blackpool
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SHOP WORKERS' union, Usdaw, has moved to counter government proposals
for legislation to expand Sunday trading, expected in today's Queen's
speech.
Delegates at the union's annual conference unanimously backed their
executive committee's call to move the focus of the anti-Sunday trading
campaign to influencing new legislation and away from simple condemnation of
shops trading illegally.
Mr Bill Connor, deputy general secretary, said the union would continue to
call for law enforcement, but delegates had to realise that large stores
would continue to trade illegally, especially over the Christmas period.
The union gave qualified support for the so-called 'rest' proposals,
formulated by Keep Sunday Special (KSS), the anti-Sunday-trading lobby. Mr
Connor said the proposals were acceptable because they meant most shops
would be closed on Sundays, law-breaking employers would face fines of up to
Pounds 50,000, and boards of directors would be held legally liable.
He criticised KSS for having little to say about Scottish shopworkers and
for suggesting that illegal traders be closed for up to 14 days, without
clarifying the position of staff during that time.
The union will press EuroFiet, the body that represents the interests of
shop workers at European community level, to join Usdaw in sponsoring a
conference on trading hours legislation.
Earlier, the union reaffirmed its support for wages councils, the bodies
that set minimum statutory pay levels for about 2.5m workers, of which more
than 1m are shop workers.
Mr Tony Blair, shadow employment secretary, told the conference he would
fight the abolition of wages councils line by line and comma by comma in the
House of Commons. He said the government had no mandate to abolish wages
councils because the Conservative manifesto did not refer to that.
</TEXT>
