FT  06 MAY 92 / International Company News: Petro-Canada returns to profit
in quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PETRO-CANADA posted a modest first-quarter profit after inventory accounting
changes. In 1991, it incurred a CDollars 598m loss including special
charges.
The profit of CDollars 32m (USDollars 26.8m), or 15 cents a share, including
proceeds from asset sales, compares with a net loss of Dollars 52m a year
earlier. Revenues were Dollars 1.1bn against Dollars 1.3bn. Cash flow from
operations doubled to Dollars 124m, or 58 cents a share. Capital spending
was halved to Dollars 97m.
The upstream division was under pressure from low oil and gas prices and
lower production. The downstream side increased sales of refined products
and reduced overheads.
The change in inventory accounting for 1992, being followed by all Canadian
integrated oil companies, inflated first-quarter earnings by 12 cents a
share.
The upstream business is being re-structured. Investment is being
concentrated in western Canada and in the east coast off-shore light oil.
Producing assets in the west will be rationalised, resulting in greater
control of core properties.
However, the net impact on production volume would be small, the company
said. But staff cuts will total 1,200 by the end of 1993.
The re-structuring will require a special charge in the second quarter.
Petro-Canada, 80 per cent state-owned, is closing nearly 1,000 retail
outlets and reducing refining capacity in the next year.
The company remains 80 per cent owned by the federal government after the
first stage of privatisation two years ago. It is trying to become more
competitive in preparation for a further privatisation step.
