<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / Major wants to end automatic honours
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR wants to overhaul the honours system with the aim of ending
automatic rewards for civil servants and others who reach a particular rank
or length of service, it emerged yesterday.
The prime minister is sympathetic to the growing criticism of the civil and
military honours, which many mandarins, MPs and members of the armed forces
receive almost by right  - rather than for their contribution to society.
Downing Street officials emphasised, however, that 'nothing is going to
happen in the immediate future'.
Mr Major believes he made a start in changing the priorities for awards in
last June's Gulf war honours list, when he deliberately put emphasis on
rewarding meritorious service regardless of rank. Reforming the honours
system would fit Mr Major's pledge to push for a 'classless' society.
Mrs Margaret Thatcher, the former prime minister, reinstituted political
honours, including hereditary peerages, for long-serving politicians.
Changes to the system would, however, be supported by many Tory MPs.
Sir Peter Emery, chairman of the Commons procedure committee, said: 'The
honours system has a role to play in British society but it should be based
on merit and the individual contribution of a person  - rather than the
length of time they have served in a particular job.'
Mr Richard Shepherd, Conservative MP for Aldridge-Brownhills, said on BBC
Radio: 'The automatic assumption that you get knighthoods or gongs is, I
think, very out of date.'
Other senior backbench Conservative MPs would also back reform of the
honours system but, perhaps looking at their own prospects, refused
yesterday to comment publicly.
</TEXT>
