<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / Doctor seeks political cure for Belfast's ills: The
difficult task facing Dr Joe Hendron in Gerry Adams' former constituency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE political landscape has changed in West Belfast, where the predominant
Roman Catholic population lives in gritty red-brick houses, in a physical
landscape not helped by bomb damage and metal grilles on traffic lights and
pub windows.
Dr Joe Hendron, the freshly elected Social Democratic and Labour party MP,
is a moderate nationalist who cheerfully provokes republican hardliners
after narrowly winning the seat on April 9. 'They are extremely hostile to
me because they were beaten in the election,' he says.
Dr Hendron, who will work within the UK political system, has replaced Mr
Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing, who would
not. Because it supports violence, Mr Adams' party is excluded from
round-table talks on the province's future which began again yesterday.
Dr Hendron estimates that he was helped by about 1,500 Protestants in
Unionist enclaves who voted tactically. Sinn Fein said those voters
supported loyalist paramilitaries; Dr Hendron says that is 'an extreme
insult'.
Smouldering tensions in his constituency flared with the murder by loyalist
terrorists last week of a 26-year-old mother, Mrs Philomena Hanna, at a
chemist's shop on Springfield Road. Dr Hendron was jostled by Sinn Fein
supporters as he visited the site. 'Hendron's voters killed Philomena,' read
posters.
If Dr Hendron, aged 59 and a GP since the 'troubles' began, was supposed to
be a conciliator, his first action, prompted by Mrs Hanna's death, was
regressive. After urgent consultations with the Royal Ulster Constabulary,
the gates along the 'peace line'  - a spiked barrier that rises as high as
bedroom windows on houses along the Protestant and Roman Catholic divide  -
were closed.
In justification, the loquacious MP shows a card he was given at an
interdenominational service after the killing. 'This was handed out to all
the people. 'The walls of separation do not reach to Heaven.' That is what I
would say.
'So many politicians are screaming 'These gates must be kept open', but they
are not living on the peace line. People are very frightened.'
A greater test will be Dr Hendron's performance over coming years.
Non-participation in the Westminster system has been ingrained among radical
Irish nationalists for decades. Dr Hendron wants to work with Northern
Ireland Office ministers to encourage investment in West Belfast, drumming
up interest in the US, Canada and elsewhere. He also wants to talk with the
police and Army about ending harassment. Mr Adams did nothing, he says.
Mr Richard McAuley, Sinn Fein's spokesman, responds: 'We have a very
well-run constituency service which provides a useful service in West
Belfast. Unlike Joe Hendron, we did not engage in making promises we could
not keep.'
Dr Hendron is also part of the SDLP delegation at the round-table talks  -
hoping to deliver a deal by which local politicians can be given real
political control.
When he canvassed on Unionist housing estates, the 1985 Anglo-Irish
Agreement  - supported by the SDLP but despised by Unionists because of the
role it gives the Irish republic  - was top of the agenda. 'I said, 'But
isn't that what the talks are about?' I said that the Anglo-Irish Agreement
is not a sacred cow.'
Success in the talks would require huge compromises with the Unionist
community. West Belfast would need much convincing.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
