<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / Channel 5 writ against TV-am
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FIVE TV, one of the companies planning to bid for the Channel 5 licence,
yesterday issued a writ against TV-am, the breakfast television company, for
alleged breach of contract.
Last week TV-am signed an agreement to bid for the franchise in a consortium
that included Time Warner, the world's largest media organisation, and Mr
Conrad Black's Daily Telegraph group. Mr Bruce Gyngell, TV-am chairman, was
to be chairman of the consortium, to be called The Entertainment Channel.
Yesterday Five TV, whose investors include Mr Moses Znaimer, founder of City
TV in Toronto, said TV-am had signed a document in January agreeing not to
invest in any other applicant for the Channel 5 licence other than Five TV.
TV-am  - which lost its ITV franchise in last year's competitive tenders  -
last night conceded that it had signed what appeared to be such an
undertaking, but by mistake.
The company said Mr Stratis Zographos, the TV-am finance director, had
signed what he thought was a normal confidentiality agreement in order to be
able to see the proposed Five TV business plan. It had then discovered a
line about not investing in a rival Channel 5 bid. It said it would defend
any legal action.
Mr Gyngell said: 'We signed what we thought was a normal confidentiality
agreement. We regard that line (about a rival bid) as a restraint of trade
and that is also senior counsel's opinion.'
TV-am is surprised at the timing of the legal action because both Mr Jeremy
Fox, the chief executive of The Entertainment Channel, and Mr David Frost,
the broadcaster and TV-am founder, have been in Toronto for talks with Mr
Znaimer about a possible merger between the two bidders.
The main choice for the Channel 5 licence may turn out to be between Five
TV, which plans a mainly city-based service, and something like The
Entertainment Channel, offering a largely national service.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
