<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / Prince Charming finds his Cinderella: Michael Heseltine
outlines his strategy for the trade and industry department
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN Mr Michael Heseltine was offered the job of trade and industry
secretary three weeks ago he chose to revive the title of president of the
board of trade.
It is a potent symbol of the political clout he has brought to a job that
had become one of the Cinderellas of successive Conservative
administrations. Already his staff refer to him simply as 'the president'.
But Mr Heseltine is also a political realist. If he is to deliver a
partnership between government and industry  - mapped out during his
political exile under Mrs Margaret Thatcher  - there will be battles to be
fought, not least with the Treasury.
So yesterday it took 30 minutes to prise from him a phrase to encapsulate
his new role in Mr John Major's government: 'My job is to help British
industry to win . . . commerce and industry to win.'
Speaking to the FT in his first interview since his appointment, Mr
Heseltine was concerned to damp speculation that he had arrived with a
bagful of instant solutions. 'I know that industrial success, commercial
success is essentially a long-term phenomenon,' he said. 'The great danger
is to try to adopt the psychology of the fairy godmother.'
He intends to build a closer relationship between government and industry  -
to establish over time what he calls an industrial strategy. Yet he is not
in the business of raising expectations that he cannot meet.
His starting point is that his advocacy of such a strategy is still
misunderstood. For others it conjures up images of 'picking winners' or
subsidies for sunset industries. He said: 'What I have always meant by an
industrial strategy is an awareness in government of the impact that
government can have on industry as a consequence of the many interfaces
between the role of government and the wealth-creating process.'
That rather long-winded explanation can be condensed as follows: since
government decisions are constantly impinging on the nation's businesses, it
is up to the DTI to introduce some coherence into the process.
Mr Heseltine promises to be a sympathetic listener. His predecessors  - Mr
Peter Lilley and Mr Nicholas Ridley  - never managed to persuade industrial
leaders that they particularly cared about anything beyond deregulation.
Their successor likes dialogue. 'I've always believed in all government
departments, including this one, that you should talk and listen carefully
to the industries, to the companies, which you sponsor.'
It was such dialogue, he added, that led to the creation of the European
Space Agency and brought lucrative contracts for British industry from the
European Fighter Aircraft project. 'Some people believe that talking to
people is a sign of weakness,' he said. 'I've never believed that.'
What about action? In his books, Mr Heseltine had after all set out in some
detail how the DTI should co-ordinate government industrial strategy. It
should replace the Treasury in the lead role at a strengthened National
Economic Development Office. A cabinet committee should be established to
take a broad view of departmental decisions which affect business.
Mergers policy should be less tightly drawn to include a wider judgment of
the national interest as well as the impact on competition of proposed
mergers and takeovers.
Here Mr Heseltine became distinctly cagey. He did not disavow completely
such ambitions but was careful to stress that they were not prerequisites.
A new cabinet committee under his direction was a matter 'for the prime
minister'. It was perfectly possible to take a strategic view of
government's relations with industry within existing cabinet committees.
On mergers policy  - perhaps the most sensitive of his responsibilities  -
he will say practically nothing. His approach to the battle for Midland Bank
between Lloyds Bank and Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation should
reveal some of his thinking. For now, though, he insists that any change in
the so-called Tebbit doctrine would require a collective decision by the
cabinet. 'I have inherited a set of (merger) policies, Until and unless any
announcements are made those policies prevail.'
So what were his immediate priorities?
Some set themselves. Britain's forthcoming presidency of the European
Community will put Mr Heseltine in the driving seat of efforts to complete
the single market. His concern was that the regulations that gave force to
that market did not end up representing a 'cloying intervention in the
marketplace'.
The legal framework had to be sufficiently flexible to adapt to a
fast-moving competitive environment. Completion of the stalled Uruguay round
of trade talks was also essential if British industry was to take full
advantage of the opportunities on the international horizon.
Closer to home, Mr Heseltine was unsure whether industry appreciated the
scale of the opportunities that were already there to be taken. His
suspicion was that the government's advice had too often been getting
through to only a 'relatively thin strata'. He would be looking closely at
improvements in the 'delivery' of advice from Whitehall.
He then came up with a phrase that is likely to figure prominently in his
public pronouncements - 'incremental excellence'. Instead of looking for
instant solutions, the government needed to look constantly and
comprehensively at all its policies to ensure that they helped to foster
wealth creation.
On one level, that meant sticking with macro-economic policies that provided
stability and fostered enterprise. On another, it meant ensuring that
policies such as those for education and training provided industry with the
quality of recruits they needed. He would also be constantly on the alert to
ensure that government decisions did not inadvertently impede industrial
success.
It was, he concluded, 'the aggregation of all these policies that adds up to
an industrial strategy'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
