<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / World Trade News: North America free trade deal could be
initialled next month
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL and NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AGREEMENT on a North American free trade area (Nafta) could be initialled as
early as next month as a result of significant headway made by negotiators
last week in Mexico City.
'It is within the art of the possible to have an agreement this summer,' Mrs
Carla Hills, the US trade representative, said in Washington yesterday. 'But
I'm not betting my next paycheck on it.'
It is understood that several chapters of the negotiating text were 'locked
up' last week. These include customs regulations, standards, principles for
services, intellectual property, textiles food safety regulations, and land
transport.
Close to agreement were tariffs, rules of origin, safeguards, and financial
services and insurance and telecommunications. There appears to have been a
breakthrough on Canadian reservations concerning local-content rules for car
production.
The main problem areas remain farm trade, especially Canada's supply
management and subsidy regimes, government procurement and energy. On the
question of Mexico's reluctance to open its energy sector to foreign
investment, advisers to the negotiators say Mexico has signalled a
willingness to compromise by opening its petrochemical sector, pipelines and
petrol stations to foreign investment.
Last week's surge in progress came after a disappointing ministerial meeting
in Montreal in early April, when some participants said talks had moved
backwards. A visit to Washington by Mr Jaime Serra Puche, Mexico's commerce
secretary, after Easter apparently revived the momentum.
'It was a very productive week,' said Mr Jules Katz, deputy trade
representative. He predicted a ministerial meeting would be scheduled later
this month 'depending on progress made'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
