<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / World Trade News: UK-led group likely to win HK bridge deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Hong Kong government is expected to announce tomorrow that a British-led
consortium has won an HKDollars 8bn (Pounds 583m) contract to build one of
the world's biggest suspension bridges. An Anglo-Japanese consortium, led by
Trafalgar House, is believed to be the successful bidder to build a 1,377m
bridge to connect Tsing Yi and Ma Wan Islands as part of the HKDollars 114bn
(in March 1991 prices) airport and related infrastructure programme.
The contract will be the biggest single one awarded so far for the colonial
government's infrastructure development of Hong Kong. As well as the
Anglo-Japanese consortium, three others were in the bidding: an all-Japanese
group and one led by the French construction company Dragages et Travaux
Publics; the third, a South Korean grouping led by Hyundai, was some
HKDollars 2bn cheaper than the Trafalgar House bid.
The HK government is expecting to be criticised by local politicians and
probably China, which had an interest in the Hyundai consortium, if it
awards the contract to Trafalgar House. Hyundai's troubles in South Korea,
where some senior executives have been accused over taxes, and the
highly-geared nature of Hyundai Construction and Engineering, the main
bidder, are understood to have concerned the HK government. It raised doubts
about the company's ability to enter into a long-term commitment to build
the bridge. The government's critics say it should never have pre-qualified
Hyundai.
UK consulting firms have done well in bidding for consultancy contracts for
the airport programme. They have done less well in previous building
contracts, but the award of the bridge to a predominantly British consortium
will be seen as favouritism in some quarters. The Anglo-Japanese group would
be asked to build one of the world's longest suspension bridges in the
shortest possible time. It will have to be completed by mid-1997, at the
latest, when the airport is expected to be opened.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
