<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / World Trade News: Olivetti Dollars 300m computer deal with
McDonald's
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OLIVETTI, the Italian computer and office equipment group, is to supply
point-of-sales computer technology to the McDonald's fast food group in the
US in an agreement worth over Dollars 300m (Pounds 169.4m).
The order, won against competition from IBM, Panasonic and NCR, is
Olivetti's biggest contract from the the US and one of the largest deals in
its history.
Under the plan, eight or nine Olivetti personal computers will be installed
in each of McDonald's 8,800 US outlets, which will be linked via local area
networks. The deal envisages the installation of over 50,000 computer
workstations, along with a variety of peripheral equipment.
The system will allow full automation both for customers, who will be served
by staff using new touch-screen terminals, and for back-office uses.
Computers in each McDonald's outlet will handle accounting, administration
and record keeping. Using the local area networks will also allow each
outlet to report regularly on its performance to McDonald's headquarters,
providing information on sales and payroll records, or receive instructions
on new menu items or prices.
</TEXT>
