<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / World Trade News: Southern EC states fight move to end tied
aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTHERN EC states have opposed a European Commission proposal, backed by
the Dutch, for the EC to remove curbs tying much of their national
development aid to purchase of goods and service within their own countries.
The first serious debate for years by EC aid ministers on the issue of
'untying' development aid ended on Monday night, with France, Spain and
Italy opposing any weakening of 'national procurement' restrictions still
attached to Dollars 10bn (Pounds 5.6bn) aid that EC states give the Third
World each year. The southern three argued that, while untying aid might
give developing countries better value for money if they could shop around
the EC for the best deal, it would cut overall aid because taxpayers in one
EC state would not want to see aid-related contracts going to the industry
of another EC state.
The Commission proposal won full backing only from Mr Jan Pronck, Dutch aid
minister, who had commissioned it when the Dutch held the EC Council
presidency last autumn. Lady Chalker, UK aid minister, with some German and
Danish support, suggested a gradual untying of aid. Ministers asked the
Commission to make a further study, but the EC executive seems unlikely to
produce a formal draft directive to abolish tied aid, as Mr Pronck has
urged. This week's debate showed France, Italy and Spain form a blocking
minority in the EC Council.
EC aid, via the Community and national budgets, amounted to Dollars 26.7bn
in 1988, (not including small amounts from Greece, Luxembourg, Spain and
Portugal which do not belong to the OECD's Development Aid Committee). Some
60 per cent is untied, including money channelled through Brussels to some
70 developing country members of the EC's Lome Convention. The remaining aid
from EC states is totally tied (requiring all contracts be placed with
companies, or contain a minimum national content, from the donor country),
or partially tied.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
