<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / Russia, India face US action over missile deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KK SHARMA
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIA and India faced the possibility of sanctions by the US after they
decided yesterday to go ahead with a Dollars 250m (Pounds 141m) contract for
the sale of Russian rocket technology for India's space programme.
The Russian decision was announced yesterday by Mr Gennady Burbulis, Russian
secretary of state, after three days of bilateral talks.
Mr Burbulis ridiculed US attempts to assume the role of global lawmaker on
missile technology and said Russia would go ahead with its contract with
India. The Bush administration warned both countries they risk US sanctions
if the deal goes through.
Ms Margaret Tutwiler, state department spokeswoman, said the US would decide
soon on its response to the rocket deal, which she said was inconsistent
with guidelines of the Missile Technology Control Regime, an accord among
western states to limit the spread of missile technology. Russia did not
sign the pact, but has agreed to abide by its provisions.
Penalties could involve suspension of access to US government contracts and
to US technology requiring export licences.
A Russian foreign ministry spokesman yesterday called for international
experts to examine the deal to show that it should not incur sanctions.
'We insist on an international expert examination of the contract to prove
that it doesn't undermine the Missile Technology Control Regime in any way,'
Mr Sergei Yastrzhembsky told reporters.
Under the deal, the Russian space agency is to sell India technology needed
to build rocket booster engines for launching communications satellites. The
US apparently feels the Indian space programme has military objectives but
Russia has rejected this view.
Russia has been collaborating with India on its space programme for a long
time. With the help of the then Soviet Union, India has launched several
satellites. Russia has now openly resisted US pressure to revise the accord.
Mr Burbulis's visit was the first by a Russian leader since the political
changes in that country. It has laid the basis for a visit to India by Mr
Boris Yeltsin later this year.
India has very close ties with the former Soviet Union and faced the
possibility of losing an important ally because Indian officials misjudged
events that led to the break-up of the Union. They have been busy ever since
trying to restore Indo-Russian relations to their former level.
Mr Burbulis's remarks at the end of his visit are reassuring to India's
ears. As well as defying the US over rocket technology, Mr Burbulis said
Russia would continue to supply defence equipment spares.
Mr Burbulis said Russia has confirmed its intention to continue defence
co-operation that the former Soviet Union had with India. He also said that
disruption of Russian crude oil supplies would end soon.
During his visit, Mr Burbulis signed a five-year trade agreement with India
which envisages payments in hard currency instead of rupees. He also offered
India a Rbs2.5bn (Pounds 14.3m) credit for supply of defence equipment and
paper.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
