</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNOR Bill Clinton yesterday took another step towards the Democratic
party's presidential nomination, winning more delegates in primary voting
and gaining the support of the US trade union movement, writes George
Graham.
Early returns and exit polls showed Mr Clinton soundly defeating former
Californian Governor Jerry Brown in Democratic primaries in Indiana and
North Carolina. He was also expected to win by substantial margins in the
District of Columbia, where polls closed later.
In Republican party primaries President George Bush was projected to have
won in Indiana and to have scored a three-to-one victory over Mr Patrick
Buchanan in North Carolina.
With Mr Bush now mathematically assured of his party's nomination, and Mr
Clinton more than 80 per cent of the way towards becoming the Democratic
candidate, yesterday's primaries were fought with little fire.
The endorsement of the AFL-CIO, the US trade union confederation, came as
little surprise as the labour movement has endorsed every recent Democratic
candidate except Mr George McGovern.
But Mr Clinton has had his differences with the trade unions, notably over
his support for the North American Free Trade Agreement which labour leaders
believe will lead to US jobs being transferred to Mexico.
