   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US banking and law enforcement authorities yesterday set in motion the
procedures needed to transfer control of First American Bankshares  - the
troubled Washington bank that was secretly controlled by the Bank of Credit
and Commerce International (BCCI)  - to an independent government-approved
trustee, writes Alan Friedman in New York.
Once the trustee is appointed he will work to facilitate the sale of First
American. The nominee as trustee is Mr Harry Albright, a former New York
State banking superintendent and former special counsel to the late
Vice-President Nelson Rockefeller.
The Washington bank has been co-operating with the Federal Reserve, the New
York district-attorney, the BCCI liquidators and the Justice Department to
achieve the trustee plan in order to sever all ownership links between BCCI
and First American.
To approve the trusteeship plan, First American has called a special
shareholders' meeting of Credit and Commerce American Holdings NV (CCAH),
the offshore vehicle controlling First American and featuring several
nominees described by the Fed last year as 'front men' for BCCI.
Among the BCCI figures being called to the meeting, to be held on May 12 in
Curacao, is Sheikh Kemal Adham, a key shareholder and the US-trained former
head of Saudi Arabia's intelligence agency.
Mr Albright will be named as the sole trustee  - enabled by a court order to
exercise the powers of an owner of all the shares of First American  - once
the plan is approved by CCAH shareholders.
