<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / O&amp;Y set to sell stake in Santa Fe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON and ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OLYMPIA &amp; YORK, the troubled property developer, yesterday unveiled plans to
alleviate its cash shortage by selling its 18 per cent stake in Santa Fe
Pacific, the Chicago-based railway, mining and pipeline group, for an
estimated Dollars 400m (Pounds 225m).
O&amp;Y announced its plans for a public offering of Sante Fe shares while 11
banks were meeting in London to decide whether to put the company's UK
subsidiary, O&amp;Y Canary Wharf Holdings, into administration under British
insolvency procedures.
The alternative to administration is a proposal, backed by the UK banks
Lloyds and Barclays, for the banks to lend Pounds 30m to allow work to
continue over the coming month at O&amp;Y's property development at Canary Wharf
in London's Docklands. Banks could not agree on the way forward but set
themselves a deadline of Thursday to resolve the matter. A banker said 'a
couple of banks are still refusing to support the proposal to put in new
money'.
Separately, O&amp;Y said it had called a meeting for Thursday with
representatives of its 15 largest creditor banks to outline long-term plans
to restructure its Dollars 12bn debt. At this meeting, to be held in London,
O&amp;Y will for the first time present a five-year business plan.
The Santa Fe deal, which is likely to raise about Dollars 400m, is meant as
a signal to O&amp;Y's banks that it is willing to make some sacrifices in its
debt restructuring by selling assets.
O&amp;Y also disclosed that it has withdrawn plans for four real estate
financings this year totalling USDollars 1.4bn.
As a result, the company said it would not pay interest totalling CDollars
17m on publicly traded bonds secured by First Canadian Place, its 72-storey
flagship building in downtown Toronto. The interest payments were due on
Monday.
Trust indentures on several of the North American buildings, including First
Canadian Place, require O&amp;Y to reserve rental income for running expenses
and debt-service payments. The company said it was preparing proposals for
the First Canadian Place bondholders which 'it hopes will be satisfactory'
to them and to their trustee.
O&amp;Y has also failed to make a smaller interest payment due on floating rates
notes secured by three Manhattan office buildings. A Dollars 6m payment on
these notes was made in April, several weeks after O&amp;Y's liquidity crisis
first surfaced.
O&amp;Y built up its stake in the original Santa Fe Pacific from mid-1987 when
it sought to diversify its real estate business. Santa Fe has since been
split into three public companies. O&amp;Y still has substantial minority
interests in the two other groups: Catellus Development, a west coast
housing developer; and Santa Fe Energy, an oil and gas producer. Meanwhile,
O&amp;Y's failure to pay interest on its publicly traded bonds is certain to
complicate its debt-restructuring efforts.
