<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / International Company News: Edgars falls short of management
forecasts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EDGARS, the clothing and footwear group in the South African Breweries
chain, unveiled an increase in earnings in the year to March, but
significantly underperformed management forecasts.
Sales rose by 11 per cent to R2.75bn (Dollars 950m) but tighter margins saw
operating profit rise by only 6 per cent to R373.2m. Attributable earnings
rose by 5 per cent to R157.5m.
The figures compare with management forecasts, made in July last year, that
sales would rise by 19 per cent and profits by 17 per cent.
Mr Mark Bower, financial director, said that management had not foreseen the
continued stagnation of the gold price, the drought, and continued high
interest rates, all of which hurt consumer spending.
Mr Bower said sales had risen by 17 per cent in the first three months, but
a precipitate decline had set in in September when official figures
indicated sectoral sales dropped by 3.4 per cent. He added that sales in the
first quarter of 1992 had been 'disastrous'.
He forecast sales and earnings growth for the year of about 12 per cent  -
in line with inflation.
Earnings and dividends per share rose 5 per cent, to 310 cents and 119 cents
respectively.
