<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / International Company News: SSAB sell-off expected to raise
SKr1.85bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SWEDISH government hopes to raise about SKr1.85bn (Dollars 312.5m) next
month by selling off its controlling stake in SSAB, the state steel company.
The divestment of the 48 per cent of equity, along with 60 per cent of
voting rights, is the first stage in the government's ambitious
privatisation programme which will include 35 Swedish companies.
The SSAB sell-off, which will run between May 19 and June 4, involves an
offer of 126,666 units to buyers. Units will consist of
government-guaranteed risk-free bonds priced at SKr14,800, including
commission, which will be redeemable in January 1994 at a value of
SKr17,000. The units also include warrants entitling the holder to purchase
100 SSAB shares at SKr170 each from January 1993 to February 15 1994. The
bond is expected to generate a guaranteed yield of at least 10 per cent,
less commission.
The Swedish government said that 55,000 of the 126,666 units would be
offered to the general public, with a further 12,000 reserved for SSAB's
employees. The remaining 60,000 units are intended for institutional
investors but foreign interests will only be able to acquire up to a quarter
of those units.
Mr Per Westerberg, the industry minister, said the offer sought to broaden
private ownership in Sweden. 'The offer should be attractive to private
individuals,' he argued. 'The state offers a risk-free saving with a good
rate of interest with the opportunity of gradually going over from saving in
bonds to saving in shares.'
However, Mr Westerberg added that the method of selling off the state's
stake in SSAB would not necessarily be used in subsequent privatisations.
'Each sale must be assessed according to its own conditions and needs. This
means that each privatisation will be unique as its practical implementation
is concerned,' he said.
</TEXT>
