FT  06 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Anglian appoints its advisers for flotation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANGLIAN GROUP, the double-glazing combine bought out for Pounds 84.5m from
BET in December 1990, has appointed advisers for its planned stock market
flotation which could value it at some Pounds 200m.
NM Rothschild is the merchant bank and James Capel the stockbroker.
The flotation, likely to take place in the summer, comes much sooner after
the buy-out than expected, as the group has achieved record profits despite
the recession.
Anglian is the leading retail double glazing company in the UK with 7-8 per
cent of the market.
The prospectus is expected to show that Anglian made operating profits of
Pounds 22.5m for the year to end-March, compared with about Pounds 15m
When BET sold Anglian it was expected to make trading profits of Pounds 10m
in the 1990-91 financial year. At the time BET bought a Pounds 30m 12 per
cent loan note from Anglian to help finance the buy-out. This was refinanced
in March.
Proceeds of the float will repay the Pounds 30m debt, and Pounds 23m of
preference capital and probably leave the company with some net cash.
</TEXT>
