<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / Lloyds could face Midland tax penalty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF LLOYDS Bank succeeds in buying Midland, the combined banks will be forced
to pay Pounds 246m in tax which would not be paid if Midland is bought by
Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation, it was claimed yesterday.
The allegation was made by Hongkong Bank's merchant bank adviser, Schroders,
in the escalating war for control of Midland.
However, Lloyds last night issued a strong assurance that the matter had
been considered and it does not believe it will incur this penalty, while
other independent tax experts said the question of whether the tax would be
paid was open to doubt.
Hongkong Bank launched an offer for Midland last month, while Lloyds has
proposed a rival bid at a higher value if certain conditions are met.
Midland's most recent accounts show that the company has tax credits worth
Pounds 207m against trading losses and Pounds 39m in advance corporation tax
for the last financial year. These losses could be offset against future
profits of nearly Pounds 740m under UK corporate tax rates. However, tax
legislation states a 'major change in the nature or conduct of a trade'
within three years of a change of ownership would lead to these tax benefits
being disallowed.
Schroders suggests that the public documents released on the proposed bid by
Lloyds appeared to commit the bank to rapid and fundamental restructuring of
Midland within three years.
'Lloyds' proposals represent a major change in trade,' it said. 'It would be
very difficult to imagine even an optimistic broker thinking the tax losses
would survive.'
Schroders also stressed that Hongkong Bank's proposals would be unlikely to
incur the same penalties as Lloyds, because it intended to maintain the bank
virtually intact as a separate business.
Lloyds is believed to have already consulted the Inland Revenue on the
issue. A source involved in the discussions said: 'The markets are the same
and the changes are pretty mundane. We have looked at this fully.'
David Barchard writes: Midland Bank's shareholders were told yesterday by
Sir Peter Walters, chairman, the bank's board believes a merger with
Hongkong and Shanghai Bank is the right strategy for the bank's future,
while a merger with Lloyds Bank would result in a combined group narrowly
focused on UK banking and involving retrenchment rather than growth.
Hongkong Bank, Page 22
Observer, Page 19
