FT  06 MAY 92 / Hongkong Bank to argue its case in letter to MPs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HONGKONG BANK will shortly open a new front in its bid for control of
Midland by writing to members of parliament to argue its case.
According to one of its advisers, the bank will keep its message 'fairly
simple' and is likely to stage follow-up meetings with MPs 'in due course'.
It is expected to argue that the interests of the UK banking sector could
best be served by an injection of new blood and the continuing presence of
four strong clearers.
The struggle for control of Midland is increasingly being conducted in the
political arena.
A week ago, MPs received a letter from Sir Jeremy Morse, chairman of Lloyds
Bank - Hongkong's rival for Midland  - arguing that the foreign bank's offer
failed to address 'the fundamental problems in the UK banking sector' and
suggesting they contact a 'Helpline' for further information.
Mr William Purves, Hongkong Bank's chairman, has already written to the
heads of relevant ministries including Mr Michael Heseltine, President of
the Board of Trade, setting out the bank's case.
Meanwhile, Ms Marjorie Mowlam, Labour frontbench spokeswoman on City and
corporate affairs, has written to both Mr Purves and Mr Brian Pitman, the
Lloyds chief executive, asking about their proposals.
She yesterday criticised the role of Mr Keith Hampson, the Conservative MP
with close links to Mr Heseltine, in offering advice to Lloyds. This showed
why it was 'difficult for politicians to take consultancies'.
