<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / Observer: Accountants in the red
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
While singing the praises of its profession, the annual report of the
Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales suggests it might do
well to learn some of the business skills its members are expected to
possess.
Glowing words describing its activities nestle among colour photos of its
London edifice at Moorgate Place. The figures at the back are rather more
disappointing: the Institute is in the red for the second year running, with
a pre-tax operating deficit of Pounds 241,000.
Income rose slightly faster than expenditure, but even with a Pounds 117,000
tax offset the growing number of bureaucratic bean-counters (up from 386 to
415 staff) were forced to knock Pounds 124,000 off their reserves.
Accountancy, its glossy magazine, and courses and conferences were among the
loss-makers.
To be fair, the losses are lower than last year, at a time when the
Institute has had additional statutory obligations. It has also launched an
ambitious campaign to persuade its members to vote to raise subscriptions.
Still, the Institute is certainly not selling off the family silver to make
up the shortfall. It purchased another Pounds 15,000 worth of silver and
antiques to add to its revalued Pounds 2.4m collection. Readers may
doubtless also be gratified to know that the value of wine held as stock has
increased to no less than Pounds 59,000.
In the meantime, members should perhaps be grateful that their Institute
refrained from merger discussions last year - and hope that it does not
indulge again for a while.
The 1990 accounts show a remarkable extraordinary item of Pounds 240,000
incurred in relation to the 'joint consultation process' for the failed
merger with the Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy - in
part payable, no doubt, to accountants acting as advisers.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
