<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / Campaign for women claims growing support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OPPORTUNITY 2000, the business-led campaign to improve the position of women
at work, now involves 20 per cent of the workforce, according to Business in
the Community, the voluntary organisation for business initiatives, which is
running it .
The campaign was launched six months ago by Mr John Major, the prime
minister. An initial 62 organisations, most of them household names, signed
up at the launch last October. Original members of the campaign included
British Airways, the BBC, NatWest Bank and J. Sainsbury.
Business in the Community said yesterday that since the launch the
recruitment of a second wave of companies had brought total membership to
110, covering 5m employees - 20 per cent of the workforce. The total
includes 20 government departments.
Each organisation that signs up to the campaign pledges to draw up goals to
monitor and improve the position of its female employees. Measures include
the introduction of flexible working patterns, policies on sexual harassment
and women-only training.
Some companies have decided to set numerical targets for the employment and
promotion of women. Other organisations have rejected such a move because of
fears of possible discrimination against male employees. A Financial Times
survey published last month found the idea of numerical targets gaining
ground among companies.
Lady Howe, who chaired the Opportunity 2000 launch committee, said: 'What
started as a drip in terms of changing attitudes towards women at work will
swell to a stream.' She said it was expected that an increasing number of
women would be appointed to company boards in the next few months.
MSF, the general technical union, said yesterday that it welcomed the
Opportunity 2000 initiative but was sceptical about the benefits to the
majority of working women 'unless it was accompanied by direct assistance
from employers'. The very people who most needed a career break - junior
staff and single parents  - could not afford to take unpaid leave, the union
said. Similarly, flexible working patterns were undoubtedly of benefit but
might be of little use if childcare arrangements were non-existent or
unaffordable.
</TEXT>
