<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 92 / Hunt puts Tory case in Wales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY MORETON, Welsh Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DAVID HUNT, Welsh secretary, advised Welsh electors yesterday to follow
the lead of the general election and return Conservative candidates at
tomorrow's local elections.
He said: 'The government has helped to transform the face of Wales, not
least through the garden festival in Ebbw Vale, which opened its doors last
Friday.
'In local government, we have sought to provide the best services at the
lowest possible cost to the taxpayer - a contrast with the Labour party's
commitment to building extravagant temples to municipal socialism at the
voters' expense.'
Mr Hunt was speaking in Newport, one of only four Welsh boroughs where
voting is being held. All are dominated by Labour. The boroughs are Swansea,
where Labour has 31 seats out of the 51 and the Conservatives nine; Port
Talbot, where Labour has 24 of the 31 seats and the Conservatives are
unrepresented; the Rhondda, where Labour has 29 of the 33 seats and the
Conservatives are also unrepresented; and Newport, where Labour has 40 seats
and the Conservatives seven.
The four boroughs are the last of the 37 in Wales that hold elections every
year, a third of the councillors retiring in rotation. All the others go to
the polls every four years, with the next elections scheduled for 1995.
There are, however, doubts over whether the counties and boroughs will go to
the polls again in their present form, as local-government reorganisation is
high on the political agenda.
</TEXT>
