FT  05 MAY 92 / Romania to ease currency controls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VIRGINIA MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUCHAREST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Romania is easing regulations on companies' hard currency holdings and is
planning to devalue the leu by about 25 per cent in the next few weeks, the
national bank has announced, writes Virginia Marsh in Bucharest.
At the same time, the government yesterday cut subsidies on many basic foods
and electricity, pushing up prices sharply, while cushioning the blow with
limited pay rises and cash handouts.
The new currency measures are part of a package of economic reforms drawn up
with the help of the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank. They
were designed to clear a backlog of import payments, restore the confidence
of the business community and encourage foreign investment, Mr Mugur
Isarescu, governor of the national bank, said.
</TEXT>
