<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / World Stock Markets (America): US equities soar as urban
violence wanes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US STOCKS soared to record levels yesterday as Wall Street reacted with
relief to signs that urban violence appeared to be waning, writes Karen
Zagor in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average was 42.04 higher at 3378.13, above its
previous record close of 3,366.50 on April 16, but the volume of just under
175m shares was not enough to signify a meaningful rally.
Advancing issues led, declining by 1119 to 611. Among other market indices,
the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 gained 4.38 to 416.91 and the Nasdaq composite
added 5.40 to 583.54. On Friday, the Dow fell 23.03 to 3336.09.
The main factor behind the gains appeared to be relief that the weekend had
not brought the feared violence in New York and other large US cities.
Big board trading was dominated by blue chip stocks. IBM climbed Dollars 1
3/4 to Dollars 92 1/2 , Ford Motor added Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 45 and
Boeing fell Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 43 1/4 .
A number of pharmaceutical company stocks saw active trading, including
Glaxo's American depository receipts, up Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 26 5/8 and
Bristol-Myers Squibb, Dollars 1 7/8 higher at Dollars 76 1/2 . Pfizer, which
agreed to sell its Coty cosmetics and fragrances business to Benckiser of
Germany for Dollars 440m, rose Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 72 1/8 .
Stronger-than-expected first-quarter earnings from Bally Manufacturing, the
casino-hotel and fitness centre owner, contributed to a 25 cents improvement
in the issue to Dollars 5 7/8 . Bally turned in first-quarter profits from
continuing operations of 8 cents a share against a loss of 33 cents a year
earlier.
Lincoln National, the seventh biggest publicly-held US insurance holding
company, rose Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 54 1/8 following first-quarter
earnings of Dollars 101.3m or Dollars 2.19 a share against Dollars 39.3m or
89 cents in the 1991 first quarter. The improved profits came in spite of a
decline in revenue to Dollars 1.92bn from Dollars 2.13bn.
Napa Valley Bancorp was one of the biggest losers on the American Stock
Exchange. The issue tumbled Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 9 1/2 after the
northern California-based bank said its board had ended talks with other
financial institutions about a possible business combination.
In the insurance sector, General Re reversed its losses after plunging
Dollars 8 7/8 in two days. Shares in the biggest US reinsurance group closed
Dollars 1 5/8 higher at Dollars 80 1/4 .
Other insurance stocks also rose, Aetna Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 42 and
Travelers Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 20 7/8 . Cigna, which reported its
first-quarter results after the close of trading, added Dollars  3/4 to
Dollars 51 3/4 .
In the secondary market, technology stocks continued to lead trading.
Seagate Technology firmed Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 16, Apple Computer rose
Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 60 1/2 and Microsoft added Dollars  1/4 to Dollars
114.
Canada
TORONTO STOCK prices closed little changed, in light trading influenced by
holidays in London and Tokyo.
According to preliminary figures, the 300 composite index gained 6.48 points
to close at 3363.54. Advancing issues outnumbed declines 273 to 258.
Seven of 14 stock groups closed higher, led by conglomerates, up 0.7 per
cent. The real estate sector had the day's biggest decline at 1.1 per cent.
</TEXT>
