<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Pinault profit halved but payout held
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PINAULT, the French industrial group which recently ran into controversy
over its bid for Au Printemps department stores, saw its net profits halved
to FFr503m (Dollars 90m) in 1991 from FFr1.05bn the year before.
The fall was attributed to a cut in exceptional earnings. Last year it made
exceptional gains of just FFr129m, compared with FFr913m in 1990 from the
sale of two industrial units and a Paris property.
Pinault, chaired by Mr Franois Pinault, one of France's more ambitious
industrialists, said its performance so far in 1992 had been 'satisfactory'
and expressed confidence about full-year prospects.
As a result the board proposed to hold the dividend at FFr9.4 a share,
despite a fall in earnings per share from FFr48.6 to FFr23.3.
Turnover rose by 11.5 per cent from FFr32.57bn to FFr36.3bn and operating
profits by 47 per cent from FFr1.58bn to FFr2.32bn.
Pinault said one of its priorities was to cut debt. The group has been left
with heavy debts of FFr15.5bn after last year's acquisitions in the retail
sector, which included the Conforama chain of furniture stores as well as Au
Printemps.
The bid for Au Printemps, originally a partial bid for two thirds of the
shares, hit the headlines when minority shareholders complained about being
excluded from the deal. The ensuing row was one of the catalysts for the
French government's on-going reform of takeover legislation.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
