<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / Interest rate cut expected today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVIDENCE of only a subdued recovery in UK consumer spending since the
general election is behind the decision by Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor,
to seek a cut in base rates. An announcement is expected today.
Weekly sales returns collated privately by a group of about 30 large
retailers are believed to have shown only a minor uplift since the April 9
election. The retailers account for total sales of Pounds 75bn a year, or
one eighth of gross domestic product.
Together with other indicators showing little movement in consumer sectors
such as the housing market, the retailing data appear to have been
persuasive. Mr Lamont and his advisers seem unlikely to wait for more
detailed evidence about the economy before sanctioning a cut of up to half a
point in base rates, held at 10.5 per cent since September.
The opportunity for a cut in base rates has been opened by the strength of
the pound since the election. It may be followed soon by reduced mortgage
rates. That could help spur an uplift in consumer spending generally, which
accounts for some two thirds of the economy.
The figures from the retailing group  - organised by the British Retail
Consortium and including Boots, Dixons, Burton and J. Sainsbury  - are not
available publicly. A member of the group said they are sent each week to
the Treasury to help it in its job of monitoring the economy.
Figures for the two weeks around Easter would have been available to Mr
Lamont in the middle of last week when he began to think seriously about
cutting borrowing rates. This was signalled in the Bank of England's
operations on money markets at the end of last week.
Retailers in the project said the figures had shown little in the way of a
recovery. 'There is no sign of a mini-boom,' said one retailing director.
The companies in the scheme account for roughly half the sales of the retail
sector. The weekly sales figures complement the monthly sales figures for
retailing collected by the government's Central Statistical Office. Even
though the CSO's system for collecting its data is better established, the
figures are out of date by the time they are published; the CSO's figures
for April will not be published until May 20.
Outside retailing, the government has had better news about a likely
recovery from the recession which began around mid-1990. But indications
from business surveys about improved confidence among companies generally
have not been enough to convince Mr Lamont that the opportunity to bring
down rates should be spurned.
In thin trading yesterday  - London markets were closed for a holiday - the
pound was little changed against the D-Mark. It was quoted in Europe at
DM2.9308, within about 2 pfennigs of its central rate in the ERM of DM2.95.
In New York it closed at DM2.9305.
Emu success at risk Page 3
Gilts calm Page 26
Currencies Page 41
</TEXT>
