<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / Treasury to endorse George for governorship of Bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR EDDIE GEORGE, deputy governor of the Bank of England, is to be endorsed
by the Treasury as a leading candidate for the governor's job when it
becomes vacant next year.
Mr George is expected to be high on a shortlist of contenders to be drawn up
by Sir Terry Burns, permanent secretary to the Treasury.
Others likely to be shortlisted include Sir David Scholey, chairman of the
SG Warburg investment bank; Sir David Walker, departing chairman of the
Securities and Investments Board; Sir Peter Middleton, chairman of Barclays
Bank and former Treasury permanent secretary; and Lord Alexander, chairman
of National Westminster Bank.
The decision will be taken this year by Mr John Major, the prime minister,
after informal talks in Whitehall and the City.
If Mr George takes the top job  - replacing Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, who
retires in June 1993 after 10 years  - it would mark the first time since
the 1960s that someone already at the Bank was appointed governor.
Mr George has a good working relationship with the Treasury, which the Bank
advises. This is even though he and Sir Terry have disagreed fundamentally
on economic policy in recent years.
Helping Mr George's candidacy is his deep understanding of financial markets
and keenness to combat inflation. But his lack of experience outside the
Bank and abrasive management style might count against him.
Choosing an insider would avoid the furore when Mrs Margaret Thatcher
appointed Mr Leigh-Pemberton, a former chairman of National Westminster and
a Tory party stalwart. This was criticised on the grounds that Mr
Leigh-Pemberton knew little about central banking. The last deputy governor
to be promoted was Lord O'Brien, governor from 1966 to 1973.
Steady Eddie, Page 6
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
