<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / Ministers' row delays 'green' measures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A WHITEHALL power struggle over control of a new anti-pollution agency has
forced the shelving of plans to include environmental legislation in the
Queen's Speech tomorrow, Ivo Dawnay writes.
Ministers had expected a 'green' bill to be among the measures, but
disagreements between the Department of the Environment and the Ministry of
Agriculture have forced a further delay.
Mr Michael Howard, environment secretary, has insisted that a new agency
should combine the powers of the National Rivers Authority, the Pollution
Inspectorate and the waste-disposal functions of councils. But Mr John
Gummer, agriculture minister, is equally determined that land drainage,
coastal defence and the activities of the rivers watchdog should fall to
him.
The dispute first surfaced last year in an unresolved clash between Mr
Gummer and Mr Michael Heseltine, now trade and industry secretary.
A 'green' bill is now likely to be tabled next year, possibly taking in
factors from next month's United Nations environment conference in Brazil
and the government's decision to reduce the timetable for cutting carbon
emissions.
</TEXT>
