   CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AT LEAST 13 people were killed yesterday in clashes between Moslems and
Christians in Upper Egypt. It was among the worst outbreaks of sectarian
violence in many years and is certain to prompt calls for heightened
security.
Egypt's Interior Ministry blamed feuding between Christian and Moslem
families over the purchase of a house in a village near Assiut.
Concern is growing about tension between the two communities, especially in
Upper Egypt. Christians account for about 10 per cent of Egypt's population
of 58m, but they are most numerous in Upper Egypt.
