<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / Thatcher may be offered earldom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MRS Margaret Thatcher is to be offered a hereditary peerage in the
dissolution honours next month, it was reported last night, Ivo Dawnay
writes.
Dissolution honours are awarded following general elections and are strictly
in the power of the departing or continuing prime minister.
But there has been speculation that Mr John Major might avoid stirring up
controversy by offering only life peerages, as was the cross-party
convention in the 1960s and 1970s.
If Mrs Thatcher accepts a hereditary earldom, giving her the right to the
title of countess, her son Mark will immediately have the right to an
honorary viscountcy and be in line to become an earl on the death of his
mother. This would allow him to sit in the Lords, unlike the baronetcy which
he will inherit from his father Sir Denis.
Downing Street last night refused to comment on the speculation, saying only
that the dissolution honours were not expected to be published before the
beginning of next month.
</TEXT>
