<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / Tough challenge for LA's task force chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR PETER UEBERROTH, named by Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley to lead
reconstruction efforts in the riot-torn city, is a man who thrives on
challenges, but many see his latest undertaking as daunting.
More than 1,600 businesses were destroyed or severely damaged in
South-Central Los Angeles in three days of violence. A total of 5,200
buildings were severely damaged.
Mr Bradley said that he chose Mr Ueberroth to head the task force because of
the superb job he did as head of the committee that organised the 1984
Olympic Games in Los Angeles, winning unprecedented support from the private
sector and ultimately recording a Dollars 215m surplus for the city.
A keen sportsman, Mr Ueberroth also served as US baseball commissioner from
1984-89, and is credited with solving the financial problems of the sport.
Mr Ueberroth, who is a staunch Republican, has been mentioned in some
circles as a potential political candidate. He is reputed to be a smart,
tough negotiator and a good organiser who is skilled at keeping the peace
but mobilising support for his cause.
He currently heads the Contrarian Group, an organisation that invests in
troubled companies, aiming to turn them around.
The son of a travelling salesman in aluminium siding, Mr Ueberroth, 54,
began his business career in Hawaii, where he was hired by the financier Mr
Kirk Kerkorian to help him establish a non-scheduled airline. At the age of
23, Mr Ueberroth founded his own charter airline service, but the venture
failed.
None the less, Mr Ueberroth went on to a successful career in travel-related
services, founding and acquiring companies that provide reservation
services, travel agencies and hotels. In 1989 he mounted a bid to acquire
the now defunct Eastern Airlines.
He has recently been in the public eye as head of the Council on California
Competitiveness, which last week delivered a damning report on the state's
business environment. which concluded that California is 'on the road to
fiscal disaster'.
'Government in California is not working at any level; it is in a state of
paralysis,' the report asserts.
In Los Angeles, Mr Ueberroth must cut through government red tape and
persuade the private sector to invest in what to many appears the most
unlikely of 'turnrounds'.
Although local government leaders welcomed Mr Ueberroth's involvement, many
remain sceptical about his ability to revive parts of the city that were
economically depressed even before last week's devastation.
Despite the scale of the task, he exudes confidence.
'We are not going to put it back the way it was. We are going to make it
better,' he said, after touring the riot-ravaged streets of South-Central
Los Angeles over the weekend.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
