<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / Leading candidates set for more poll victories
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN ANTONIO, TEXAS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush and Governor Bill Clinton seem set to win substantial,
three-state victories today in their parties' primaries.
Just as in Pennsylvania's primary last week, today's votes in North
Carolina, Indiana and the District of Columbia have generated little heat.
Mr Bush has formally wrapped up his party's nomination, and Mr Clinton, who
has already won more than 70 per cent of the delegates he needs, is now
behaving as the Democrats' de facto nominee.
This robs their two surviving challengers  - Mr Pat Buchanan, the right-wing
television commentator, for the Republicans, and Mr Jerry Brown, the former
governor of California, for the Democrats  - of any realistic claim to be
still in contention.
Mr Buchanan is staging his last stand in North Carolina, hoping to embarrass
Mr Bush by at least partially emulating the 1976 success of Mr Ronald Reagan
against incumbent President Gerald Ford.
North Carolina boasts a large body of conservative voters who have
consistently re-elected Senator Jesse Helms  - possibly the most right-wing
senator  - but Mr Helms has backed Mr Bush, although with little evident
relish.
On the Democratic side, Mr Brown seems unlikely to make much of a dent in Mr
Clinton's ability to garner votes in the south; and opinion polls suggest he
will not fare much better in Indiana or the District of Columbia.
Recent polls show Mr Clinton winning 60 per cent of the Democratic vote in
North Carolina, against Mr Brown's 13 per cent, and 55 per cent in Indiana
compared with Mr Brown's 15 per cent. At the weekend Mr Clinton also picked
up delegates from caucus votes and party conventions in Guam, Texas and
Missouri.
But the same polls suggested that Mr Clinton would come in third in both
states in a three-candidate general election against President Bush and Mr
Ross Perot, the Texas businessman who is seeking to enter the election as an
independent candidate.
Mr Perot yesterday urged caution in accepting a free-trade agreement with
Mexico, Reuter adds from San Antonio, Texas.
He said the US was in a vulnerable position. 'Just to suddenly throw the
doors open will really wipe out the jobs of millions of people in this
country,' he said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
