<PROFILE>_AN-CEEBIADBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920505
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / German interest rates put Emu success at risk
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH, European Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HIGH German interest rates are jeopardising many EC countries' chances of
meeting the stiff fiscal targets set for European monetary union (Emu) at
the Maastricht summit.
The objectives were laid down as the crucial criteria to decide which
countries could participate in Emu at the end of the decade.
However, sluggish European economic growth  - a consequence of high interest
rates across the continent  - is leading to a sharp increase in EC
public-sector borrowing this year. This compounds the economic obstacles in
the path of Emu, which is already facing larger than expected political
hurdles because of the growing reluctance of the German population to
countenance abandoning the D-Mark.
Underlining a growing mood of questioning about Germany's commitment to Emu,
one senior European central banker said at the weekend: 'There's no doubt
that they (the Germans) are having some second thoughts.'
Economic expansion in most western European countries is expected to remain
in the 1-2 per cent range this year, after an average of only 1.2 per cent
last year.
Dampened growth automatically widens public-sector deficits by increasing
social security spending and reducing tax revenues. This is raising doubts
over whether a majority of European countries will be able to fulfil the
fiscal targets by the time of the earliest date for Emu in 1997.
Because of bloated deficits caused by unification, some experts at the
Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) in Paris
calculate that Germany itself may not be able to meet the fiscal targets.
A considerable economic pall has been cast by the Bundesbank's policy of
keeping interest rates high to dampen the inflationary effect of steep
German public-sector deficits. These deficits have been driven up by
large-scale transfers of public funds from west to east Germany.
Reflecting concern about the growth of German money supply well outside the
Bundesbank's target range, the central bank seems likely to keep its
discount and Lombard interest rates unchanged at least until the autumn.
They were raised to 8 per cent and 9 3/4 per cent respectively - the highest
levels since the 1930s  - a week after the Maastricht meeting.
The Maastricht fiscal policy criteria require that countries bring their
budget deficits down to no more than 3 per cent of gross domestic product.
The outstanding stock of government debt is required not to exceed 60 per
cent of GDP.
Andrew Fisher adds from Frankfurt: Mr Hans Tietmeyer, deputy president of
the Bundesbank, reaffirmed yesterday that the bank had no intention of
cutting interest rates for the moment, as inflation was 'unacceptably high'
and money supply growing too fast. The bank's goal was an inflation rate of
2 per cent or less.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
              EUROPE'S STRUGGLE FOR CONVERGENCE
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                 Inflation (A) Deficits (B) Debt (C) Int Rates (D)
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Target                4.4          -3        60.0         10.8
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Belgium               3.2          -5.7     131.5          9.3
Denmark               2.4          -1.7      59.6          9.3
France                3.1          -1.7      47.1          9.0
Germany               3.5*         -3.2      43.4          8.5
Greece               18.9         -17.9      85.2         23.3
Irish Rep             3.2          -2.7     113.0          9.2
Italy                 6.4         -10.1     103.8         13.0
Luxembourg            3.1          -1.9       6.9          8.1
Netherlands           3.9          -3.5      79.8          8.7
Portugal             11.3          -5.4      64.7         17.1
Spain                 5.9          -3.9      45.3         12.4
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Figures in bold indicate statistics which meet Maastricht criteria.  A
annual change in consumer prices, must not be more than 1 1/2 points
above three lowest EC inflation rates; B general government deficit
(central government, regional and local government, social security
funds) as percentage of GDP, must not exceed 3 per cent; C general
government debt as a proportion of GDP, must not exceed 60 per cent; D
yields of long-term government bonds, must not exceed yields of the
three lowest-inflation countries by more than 2 per cent. *Inflation
figures for Germany are west Germany.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: EC commission, OECD, national statistics
