<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / Leaders in Bonn reject talk of grand coalition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TALK of a grand coalition between Christian Democrats and Social Democrats
to tackle Germany's daunting unification problems is spreading through Bonn,
in spite of denials from all the key party leaders that they want anything
of the kind.
Mr Gerhard Schroder, Social Democrat (SPD) prime minister of Lower Saxony
and one of the party's leading state 'barons', called yesterday for just
such a solution on the grounds that the current Christian Democrat
(CDU)-Free Democrat (FDP) coalition of Chancellor Helmut Kohl was no longer
capable of running the country.
Mr Theo Waigel, finance minister and leader of the Bavarian-based Christian
Social Union (CSU), sister party of the CDU, said in an interview with Stern
magazine that the coalition partners must solve their differences before the
summer break, or they might fall apart.
And Mr Wolfgang Kubicki, state leader of the FDP in Schleswig-Holstein, gave
them less: just six weeks to decide common policies on the key questions of
budget cuts, dealing with asylum seekers, financing old-age care, and
fighting crime, or face collapse.
Without the FDP, the CDU and CSU would lack a working majority in the
Bundestag by 13 votes: they currently have 319 seats in the 662-seat lower
house of parliament. The SPD could not put together a rival government
without at least two partners, the FDP and the Progressive Democrats, the
successor-party to the Communists in East Germany. The SPD has 239 seats,
the FDP 79, the PDS 17 and the Greens just eight.
The only obvious alternative solution would be a grand coalition of CDU/CSU
and SPD, as was formed in 1966.
It is a solution so far flatly rejected by both Mr Kohl and the entire
national leadership of the SPD, which heard Mr Schroder's proposal yesterday
and rejected it.
The one sign of action, however, is that the SPD leadership has agreed to
meet the government partners for cross-party talks on May 27  - to discuss
the financial burden-sharing between the central government and the states,
and probably other key differences which might require a constitutional
change to resolve: asylum and ratification of the Maastricht treaty on
European union.
</TEXT>
