<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / Craxi caught in cross-fire of Milan scandal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE effects of the two-month-old Milan corruption scandal, centring on
pay-offs for public contracts being funnelled to political parties, have
finally reached Rome and are likely to influence the choice of Italy's next
president.
At the same time the Milan municipal council is expected to resign as a
result of the scandal, and an interim council of 'technicians' be appointed
under Mr Giampiero Borghini, the socialist mayor.
Milan magistrates are expected to decide this week whether to make a formal
request to parliament for the waiving of immunity on Mr Carlo Tognoli, the
outgoing Socialist minister of tourism, and Mr Paolo Pillittieri, returned
as a Socialist deputy in the April 5 general elections.
Mr Tognoli, mayor of Milan from 1976-86, and Mr Pillittieri, mayor of the
city from 1986 until late last year, have been notified by magistrates that
they are under investigation for alleged illegal receipt of funds. Both men
have denied any wrong-doing.
They are the most senior figures yet to be involved in the investigation and
Mr Pillittieri is the brother-in-law of Mr Bettino Craxi, the Socialist
leader.
Since the arrest on February 17 of Mr Mario Chiesa, a prominent member of
the Socialist party and allegedly the central figure in a large municipal
corruption network channelling funds to political parties, almost 20 people
have been charged with corruption and abuse of office.
Magistrates appear to be establishing an ever-widening network around Mr
Chiesa, head of the Pio Albergo Trivulzio, the city's oldest charitable
institution. With the arrest last week of two senior figures belonging to
the Democratic Party of the Left (PDS), the charges of corruption now
include the whole ideological spectrum.
A former Christian Democrat party official has also been charged with
corruption.
However, the main political attention has focused on the Socialist party and
its leader, Mr Craxi. Mr Craxi has long made Milan his power base and the
city has been the show-case of post-war Socialist administration. The people
now under investigation have all been closely connected with Mr Craxi.
Even though the charges have not been proven, Mr Craxi's reputation has been
badly damaged. Mr Eugenio Scalfari, the editor of Italy's largest selling
daily newspaper, La Repubblica, and an old enemy of Mr Craxi, said over the
weekend the Socialist leader was no longer qualified to stand either for the
presidency or the premiership.
Before the April elections Mr Craxi had seemed the person most likely to
head the next government. In a damage limitation exercise, the Socialist
party has appointed a special commission of inquiry into the activities of
its Milan section.
But if magistrates decide to press for charges against Mr Tognoli and Mr
Pillittieri the damage will be hard to limit. Once a request to waive
immunity has been placed before parliament, the process normally takes a
month to consider.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
