<DATE>920505
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / Reform of pension fund use resisted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANY government move to prevent companies from using their pension fund
surpluses for their own benefit is likely to result in significantly lower
levels of corporate contributions and threaten the security of schemes,
according to finance directors of Britain's largest companies.
A report to be published shortly by the 100 Group of finance directors,
after a survey of its members, is the first formal response from British
industry to proposals for pension fund reform aired in recent months.
Co-operation from employers who sponsor pension schemes is seen as critical
in implementing any plans for reform. The companies surveyed account for
roughly Pounds 97bn in pension fund assets, about a third of all those in
the UK.
Since revelations that more than Pounds 400m has disappeared from pension
funds controlled by the late Mr Robert Maxwell, UK lawmakers have been
besieged by public demands for an overhaul of UK pensions law.
The cross-party parliamentary select committee on social security, after
months of hearings, has called for legislative changes to improve pension
fund security.
While some groups have called for laws to prevent employers from using
scheme surpluses, the committee failed to address the matter, saying it
required further study. The report by the 100 Group shows that, despite
concerns that reform would hobble companies' ability to use surpluses for
themselves, the majority of large employers believe that surpluses should be
shared with workers.
Of 91 companies responding to a questionnaire, 74 said they planned to use
funds to improve benefits to members, and only six said they would not do
so.
An equal number said they would also use the surplus either to take a
contributions holiday or repay some of it to the company.
The study showed a wide degree of support for some elements of pension
reform that have been proposed by the select committee. In particular, the
finance directors are calling for 'rigorous internal control and
accountability in pension scheme management'.
The study, the broadest of its kind in the UK, found several significant
trends. Particularly, there is a growing concentration of pension funds in
the hands of a small number of fund managers. The study noted that five
internally managed funds and six UK fund managers accounted for more than
half of all the funds surveyed.
'A limited number of major fund managers control an increasing part of the
share capital of UK companies. The effect of this is yet to be seen in
practice but it may militate against short-termism,' the study noted.
</TEXT>
