<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / Mellor to overhaul policies at new heritage department
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DAVID MELLOR is determined to launch a rigorous review of policy in every
area of activity covered by his new National Heritage department.
This means that everything from funding of the arts to sport, tourism and
broadcasting will be given a fresh look by the potentially high-profile
department created after the general election.
Mr Mellor said in an interview with the Financial Times: 'I can't think of a
single area where there is an existing policy that doesn't have to be taken
down, inspected, scrutinised and at the very least polished up and probably
frankly dismantled and put together again.'
The former chief secretary to the Treasury insisted, however, that he
intended to seek consensus and was already planning to bring in 'a whole
host of people' for talks on future initiatives.
'I accept my responsibility to give a lead but I believe the record shows
that I am someone who is capable of stimulating a debate by bringing in the
best brains from the groups affected and outside,' he said.
One of his main tasks, which include setting up a national lottery designed
to raise Pounds 1bn a year and planning the millennium celebrations, will be
renegotiation of the BBC's Charter. Mr Mellor said neither he nor Mr John
Major, the prime minister, was about to take an axe to the BBC. He said he
did want to stimulate the widest possible public debate about the
corporation's future role and funding.
Everyone, Mr Mellor said, had wanted a powerful arts ministry rather than a
sideshow, yet they wanted him to be taken to the vet first and neutered
before having anything to do with them.
'If groups want to be represented by a cabinet minister who enjoys the
full-hearted confidence of the prime minister as a major player in his
administration they have to expect that an element of dynamism has to be
injected,' he said.
The FT Interview Page 44
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
