<DOCNO>FT922-9951</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEEBIACLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920505
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 92 / International Bonds: Eurosterling sector may be in need of a
short rest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EUROSTERLING bond market has held up well in the face of more than
Pounds 2bn of supply since the UK election. The bullish sentiment which
still pervades the market is exaggerated by grim conditions in most other
bond markets. But some inventory is beginning to mount up, and the market
may be in need of a short rest.
The market has coped with heavy supply because other factors have combined
to attract crucial groups of investors to the market at the same time.
Most bond fund managers were substantially underweight in sterling before
last month's election. Since then, they have switched not just to neutral
but to overweight positions.
A month ago, the sterling bond market was beset by political uncertainty.
Now, it is one of a shrinking band not wracked by political problems.
At the same time, European retail investors, reluctant to buy the market due
to previous negative experiences with the currency, have regained some
confidence. Sterling's strength since the election, and the prospect of a
move to the narrow band within the exchange rate mechanism have helped
convince some, like the Germans, who are no longer preoccupied with their
own domestic bond market, to look again.
The sterling market is well acquainted with the alternation of feast and
famine which characterises most Eurobond market sectors.
'Sterling, like Canadian dollars, is still a hot-money sector,' said one
banker. 'It's the flavour of the month, then it's dead for two.'
There is as yet little sign that the recent crop of issues represents
anything more than the latest burst of activity. But bankers are keen to
develop a corporate bond market in sterling, akin to, or at least modelled
on, the US corporate bond market. To this end, many are developing stronger
credit research capacity. The theory is that there is a long-term trend away
from bank lending and towards funding in the bond markets.
'Banks no longer want to lend to corporates in sufficient size. The advent
of capital adequacy rules is having a strong impact on the availability of
loans,' one banker said. Some companies, realising that loans are much
harder to come by, are keener to tap bond markets.
Most of the latest batch of issues have been launched by UK companies. Among
the crop was an ambitious Pounds 500m deal for Hanson, the largest deal in
the sector to date, which lead manager Credit Suisse First Boston claims to
have placed. But other bankers suggest there is inventory around, and other
paper, like Finland's Pounds 150m deal via Baring Brothers, is not yet fully
placed.
The preponderance of UK companies in the market is strongly linked to the
availability of swaps. Swap spreads have been tight for some time, making
the market unattractive for borrowers which do not have a fixed-rate
sterling funding requirement.
Swap spreads from five through to 10-years are around 30 basis points above
gilt yields.
So a strong company which would have to offer bonds at a spread of, say, 80
basis points above the gilt yield would have to pay at least 50 basis points
above the London interbank offered rate.
Of last week's new issues, only the National &amp; Provincial Building Society's
five-year deal via JP Morgan, which took advantage of a slight widening of
swap spreads, was swapped. However, while companies are eschewing
floating-rate funding at the levels available, many do not want to lock in
fixed-rate levels yet, since they expect rates to fall further.
Indeed, perceived signalling by the Bank of England on Friday of a further
reduction in rates is likely to deter corporate treasurers further.
The tightness of swap spreads has thus limited the market to UK companies,
for the most part, reducing the availability of sovereign and supranational
paper.
The lack of top quality paper was highlighted last week by the success of a
Pounds 200m 10-year Eurobond for the European Investment Bank, launched by
Salomon Brothers, which offered a meagre 9 basis point spread above the
comparable gilt yield. Not only was the issue snapped up by investors, but
the spread has subsequently tightened to five basis points.
In fact, the performance was reflected in other sovereign and supranational
sterling Eurobonds, which tightened three to four basis points relative to
gilts last week.
Otherwise, Eurosterling spreads have been steady, a positive sign given the
strong performance of the gilts market which the Eurosterling sector
normally lags.
</TEXT>
